>    * Plus, a nice GUI interface

I assume that this means things like pull-down menus as opposed to
keyboard commands.  This is probably a good idea, especially since we are
basically out of letters for new features.  In fact, "hook" was given its
name because H was one of only 4 letters that hadn't been used yet.  We
wanted to call it "merge," but M was already taken.
 
>   Okay, this may be a little ambitious, but the hardest part of the program 
> is the interface.  Once that's written, the rest should be easy.  Of 
> course, it'd be nice to just write it for X instead of DOS, but I do want 
> this to be used.

Here is a word of warning.  It took a very long time to get the program
into the state it is in now.  Martin wrote the first version over a series
of months.  The second version was a result of Martin and I working
together almost every afternoon for a couple of hours for an entire
semester.  The point is that this is no small project.  I guess what I'm
trying to say is that if you think you may not have time to finish the
whole thing, it might be wise to just make piecewise improvements to the
current program.  Then, your work won't be wasted.

You could convert routines to C one at a time.  For example, the animation
compiler and the continuity parser/editor.  The problem with this is that
most of the historical difficulties will be left intact.  Well, you have
to decide whether it's worth it.

I agree that if you write it for X, you will be wasting your time.

>   So let me know if you have any suggestions.  Also, if you would like, I 
> can mail you the copies of the program when I get anything usable done.

Please let me know when you come to specific ideas about changes so that I
can give you my opinion of them.  I've tried to guess your ideas in these
letters, but I'd like to hear more of your thoughts.

Dan


From dci@math.uchicago.edu Tue Dec 13 13:05:25 1994
