> 
>    I just thought you might be interested to know that during break I'm 
> going to begin the task of rewriting CalChart.  While it will be a while 
> before I get past the lowlevel parts of interfacing the hardware and 
> reading the files, I'm curious if there are any suggestions you have.  

The first thing you should do is call Martin Haye.  Last I heard he was
living in Woodland out near Sacramento.  I'd guess his number is in the
alumni database.  I haven't talked to him in a while, but he may be
interested in giving you a hand.  Certainly, he can give you a LOT of
technical advice.

A little background on him.  He was a junior transfer and was only in the
band for two years (89-90).  He played mello, which is how we became
friendly and how I got involved with CalChart.  I'm quite pleased that the
program continues to be "owned" by mellos.  He is a very nice guy, and I'm
sure that he will be glad to talk to you.

> Here are a few of the changes I'm planning on:
>    * Network compatibility (using C will take care of this)

It would be nice to be able to use more than one machine at a time.

>    * Direct printing (including finishing the printing program I wrote)

This is something that we always meant to do, but at the time we wrote the
code, the laser printer was in the CRH computer room, so there was no point.

>    * Shows saved in a single file, and using much less disk space

And access will be quicker, too.  Sometimes there is a fair delay while
the hard drive does its business.

>    * Easy portability to other platforms (although this isn't a huge
>        concern, a good design will make even the DOS version easier)

It's just aesthetically pleasing to have an adaptable program.

>    * Elimination of animation files

How are you going to deal with this?  The reason for the animation files
is that it takes such a long time to calculate animation each time.  Thus,
as long as you don't make any changes, the data only has to be constructed
once.  The problem with this is of course disk space.  But responsible
ADMpoops always keep a clean directory....  :)

>    * View a show from different sides (probably just east or west, maybe 
>        perspective, but I'm not sure if that will be worth the trouble-
>        I may have it write a file to load the show into a 3D animation
>        program and render it- this will be easier and look better, but 
>        will probably take a day or so to render)

We spent a lot of time discussing whether this was worthwhile.  We thought
about inputting viewpoint by giving a seat number in the stadium. 
However, to make the perspective views really useful, you can't assume
that the bandsmen are points, or even vertical lines.  They would have to
be more or less human shaped (they could be boxes).  We realized that this
one feature would probably be nearly as complicated as the rest of the
program put together.  Since the usefulness to stunt seemed miniscule, we
decided to scrap the idea. 

East or west viewing would be a good idea.  It could be implemented very
easily even in the current version.  It's not a GREAT thing, but it is a
small improvement and it's easy to do.  there should be a flag carried in
the data for a show describing it as an alumni show or a student show, so
that the animation subroutine knows which direction is default for that show.

>    * Allow copying stuntsheets to a different place in the show

This can be done by renaming files and playing around with the SHOW.MAS
files, but it can't be done from within the program.  I agree that it
would be very useful.  It never got added for historical reasons. 
Originally, we meant the program to be a verification tool, not a tool for
ongoing creation.  We expected to have a paper copy of a show, and we
would just put all the data in.  In this situation, there was no need to
reorder stuntsheets at will.  Nowadays, it would be very useful.

>    * Allow renumbering a show without splitting it and using hook

We thought about this idea, but we finally decided that perhaps the
easiest way for the user to assign the correspondence for relabeling was
to create a duplicate stuntsheet with the new labels.  Thus, splitting and
hooking were essentially the solution we were looking for.  can you think
of a simpler way.  I would hate to have to type in 150 labels on the keyboard.

>    * Use VGA for better resolution

not much to be said about this idea.  we spent a LONG LONG time playing
with colors to see what looked the best for backgrounds, highlights,
labels, etc.  I'm telling you this because it may not be worth your time
trying out new color schemes since you will probably end up with the same
one we chose.

>    * Changes in the user interface? (I think it would be more intuitive
>        to select points, then change their symbol, move them, do a genius 
>        move, etc.)

I could talk about this forever.  Of course, this is the most essential
part of the whole program.  Our interface is probably not ideal because it
developed over time.  We kept making improvements to what we already had,
but we never really started over from scratch.  I'm not so sure that
selecting points and THEN selecting an operation would be good. 
Generally, a user does a whole bunch of similar tasks, then he does a
whole bunch of a different kind of similar tasks, etc.  It would be a
REALLY big pain if I was setting points by hand, and every time I selected
a point, I had to tell the program that I now wanted to move it.  Much
better to tell the program that I am about to make a whole bunch
of moves now.

Maybe you could combine the two aspects by allowing a user to "lock" in a
particular operation.  This operation would be applied to every selected
point until the user unlocks the setting.

This is the ONE idea you should keep in mind when designing the interface.
Over 75% of the use of CalChart comes in moving points and getting the
animation to work properly.  Your interface should be designed to make
these tasks as easy as possible, even if it makes other things slightly
illogical or more cumbersome.

Selecting points (we called it "blocking") was a major concern for us.  Of
course, rectangular blocking is the most useful, but diagonal blocking is
also quite useful.  Ideally, there should be three ways of selecting
points.  1: click on an individual point; 2: click-and-drag a rectangular
region; 3: click-and-drag the perimeter of the region you want ("lasso").

>    * Add more commands, like GV, SHNSEW (FMSH NS/EW)

Continuity commands are fairly easy to add to the current version. 
Basically, all you have to do is describe the movement in terms of
commands that already exist. Even if you don't actually complete this
project, these commands should be added to the program.

Rather than add a command called SHNSEW, I suggest that you change
FOUNTAIN to take a <stepsize> variable.  If someone wanted a show high
NSEW, he could just use fountain.  Otherwise, you'll need to create a
JSNSEW, etc.  This would follow the general protocol for continuity
commands.  This protocol is that there are essentially two kinds of
commands.  The first kind is generally very cumbersome to use, but it is
also very flexible.  The second kind is just a very useful specific case
of a command of the first kind.  For example, NSEW (second kind) is a
special case of FOUNTAIN (first kind).  FMTO (second kind) is a special
case of MARCH (first kind). 

>    * Maybe add drawing tools for the printed copy? (arrows and the like)

We thought this would be useful, but we never got around to it because
there were always more important things to do.

I've got to run right now, but I'll be back soon with more comments.

Dan


