From: Dan Isaksen <dci@math.uchicago.edu>
Message-Id: <199501252359.RAA25384@dent.uchicago.edu>
Subject: brief history of calchart
To: evidali@uclink2.berkeley.edu, gmeeker@uclink.berkeley.edu
Date: Wed, 25 Jan 1995 17:59:24 -0600 (CST)
Cc: dci@dent.uchicago.edu (Dan Isaksen)
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL13]
Content-Type: text
Content-Length: 6944      
Status: RO
X-Status: 


Gurk: This is the history I promised you yesterday.

Erin: I thought you might be interested in a little historical perspective
on this.  In particular, note the two paragraphs highlighted with >'s.

Dan

-------------

Martin Haye originally had an idea for a computer program in fall
89 because he was a bad music marker.  He always made mistakes, and then
he was hopelessly confused at rehearsal.  What he wanted to do was input
his location on ss 1 and what he thought his continuity throughout the
show should be.  Then the computer would output the resulting location on
the last stuntsheet.  He could then compare this projection with his
actual location.  If it matched, then most likely there was no mistake, at
least not a large one.

This idea naturally led to more general and powerful ideas.  Martin went
to Briggs with his idea: input the show into the computer, and then print
out 144 text listings of continuity - one for each person.  Save everyone
the trouble of deciphering stuntsheets.

> Actually, stunt correctly did not think much of this idea.  They realized
> that the first rehearsal is NOT on Tuesday.  The REAL first rehearsal
> occurs when someone works his way through the poopsheets, looking for his
> spot, reading the continuity instructions, making arrows.  By the time
> bandsmen show up for rehearsal, they ALREADY are somewhat familiar with
> the show. 

However, Martin and stunt came to an agreement on a project that would be
very useful.  Input the points into the computer, and print out
nice-looking stuntsheets.  No more tedious pooping parties, no more messy
unreadable handdrawn sheets.

Along the way, it was realized that animation would be fairly easy and
rather useful.  The original intended use of animation was strictly as a
tool for finding charted collisions and reworking flows to avoid them. 

Nowadays, we don't even realize how much of a pain in the butt pregame
rehearsals used to be.  Bandsmen getting in each other's way, stunt
members trying to mentally work out solutions right there on the field. 
The result was really bad continuity like: MT2W, HS2S, MT4W, HS2N, MT2W,
HS16E to position.  These problems are now solved in the computer room
long before the first rehearsal.

So, this determined the whole outlook for the first version: print out
nicelooking sheets and check for collisions.  The interface was designed
with this in mind.  It was expected that people would copy data into the
computer from handdrawn sheets, type in continuity, and then test for
collisions.  If everything worked well, then a printout could be made.

The first version was ready to be used for Fall 90, and ALL of the shows
that year were submitted on paper.  Subsequently, Martin put in the data
and checked for collisions.  About halfway through the season, Greg Jones
(DM90) announced that Martin was looking for help, so I volunteered.  We
worked together for the rest of the season on this task.

The basic method was: about a week before the first rehearsal, get the
sheets from the DM desk, input the data, look for collisions.  Tell stunt
about any problems.  Print out the sheets in time to be sent to the
printers.  That's all there was to it.

In the fall, we learned from experience what worked easily and what was
too cumbersome.  In Spring 91, we made some major changes, primarily to
the user interface, to make the program more efficient for what we
expected to be using it for.  Geniusmove was invented because we kept
having to move these parallelograms one row at a time.  We increased
flexibility of labeling and symbols for cosmetic reasons.  Also, we made
many changes to the continuity assignments and added many new continuity
commands to increase the range of animatable flows.

All along, we fully expected that charters would still be using paper
during their initial creative stages.  In fact, we wrote in the manual
that we thought the program was NOT particularly useful for original work.
In our opinion (expressed in the manual), it was much better to mentally
work out ideas and maybe try them out with the animator to see how they
looked.  The program should only be used as a final check for accuracy.

As an example, I recall that "Insert a sheet" was added fairly late in the
creation of the second version.  We always started at the beginning of a
set of sheets and worked our way through to the end.  Who would ever want
to skip around?  When people started testing their flows with the
animator, we decided that insert might be useful for them.  To us, Insert
is obviously very useful.  But our perspective is different now.

Another example is Hook.  It can be used to relabel, but only in a very
awkward way.  This is because we never intended it to be used for that
purpose.  We wrote Hook (the last major change, by the way) because
different stunt members had written different parts of spring show, and we
wanted to put them all together.  Only afterwards did we realize that
relabeling was possible.

So, we were somewhat surprised when stunt members started doing all their
work at the computer.  This new pattern has caused some changes in the
general flavor of the band's charting.  In particular, stunt members have
become reluctant to try flows that are not animatable on the computer.  I
suppose they fear that the flows may be disasters, and they won't know
until too late.

> Even worse, even flows that are possible but merely difficult to animate
> tend not to be used.  At least a few times, I have seen a stuntmember
> say, "Well, I guess the other way is easier, and it's good enough" (with
> respect to a choice between a more complicated but better flow and a
> simpler flow).  My only > hypothesis is that this is simply a case of
> "path of least resistance."

> Occasionally, I have seen a stuntmember working on a new flow between two
> fixed sheets.  He tries NSEW and hopes for the best.  No collisions! 
> Great, that's the continuity.  But no consideration was given to what the
> flow itself looked like!  Obviously, this is not a good thing.

This explains why the second version has so many apparent shortcomings. 
Such obvious features as reordering stuntsheets are missing.  Some
features are possible but hopelessly cumbersome (like relabeling with Hook).

The third version is going to make HUGE improvements in these neglected
areas.  Now that we know what the program is actually used for, its
interface can be tailored to suit these needs.

>From the experience of the shortcomings of the second version, it is clear
that a very open perspective should be taken with the third version.  I
strongly recommend creating features of doubtful use, just in case someone
wants to use them.  Also, there is absolutely nothing wrong with having
more than one way to do something.  Most likely, at least one of them will
be efficient for any particular purpose.  My all-encompassing single word
of advice is "Generalize!"




