> 
> Ahh, that helps clear some things up.  I guess I should talk to Erin or 
> Rune to see what the best system of lines is.

See my letter to you, rune, and erin.
 
> 
> I'm really starting to like this design, but I think it can be improved a 
> little.  I think selecting a new group of points should be a little 
> easier.  So if you have points selected already, you can reselect points 
> without hitting a key.  If you don't click on a point, then you can drag 
> out a region of points to select.  If you click on a point with the left 
> button you can move the group as described above.  This doesn't work for 
> other transformations though, because you might want to mark a location that 
> a point doesn't occupy.  Wait, I've got it.  You can click on a point, 
> since that will probably be the common case, or you can select the 
> transformation, and then go into the transformation mode, where you 
> aren't require to use a point.  Actually, if you can specify things like 
> shears by two parallel motions, you can require that the movements are 
> points.  Okay, so if no points are selected, and you click with the right 
> button, you get smart move.  If some are selected, you go into the 
> transformation mode.  You can keep moving around these control points 
> until you like it.  Then press return to execute it.  ESC backs out.  
> This sounds pretty good to me.

I still think that we don't quite have the same mental picture of what is
going on.  I'll try to explain again what I'm thinking, with a few minor
changes (improvements, theoretically) from my last explanation.

First of all, let's permanently establish some terminology so that we can
understand each other.  Part of our problem is that our language is
ambiguous.  Anything that appears in quotes can be considered as a
permanent definition.  "Man" is a little circle with a label.  "Point" is
ANY location on the field, occupied by a man or not.  "Action" is
something that happens to a set of men, such as label flip, change symbol,
translate, rotate, geniusmove.  Note that a set can consist of a single
point.  Thus, normal individual move and smartmove are actions.  "Icon" is
something off of the field that can be selected for some purpose.

You sit down at the computer and start working on the show.  You've got a
stuntsheet in front of you.  If you leftclick on a man, it will
temporarily disappear.  When you leftclick again, it will reappear at the
current cursor location.  This is called "individualmove."

If you rightclick on a man, it will be immediately moved by "smartmove."
The new location is calculated as the next term in the linear sequence
generated by the destinations of the two most recent individualmoves or
smartmoves.

If you leftdrag, you will "rectaselect" (rectangular select).  If you
rightdrag, you will "lassoselect." At this point, we have not yet decided
exactly what will happen if you rectaselect or lassoselect WHILE some
points are already selected.  Either the original selection will
disappear, or the new selection will be NOTed with the old selection.
 
If you click on an icon while some points are selected, the corresponding
action will be executed on the selected set.  Some actions will occur
immediately: label flip, autocont, etc.  Some actions might require more
information: translation, rotation, geniusmove, etc.

If you do choose an action that requires more information, the program
expects this new information to be entered immediately.  The next inputs
will be interpreted as information to explicitly define the action to be
executed.  The actual method of inputting this data will be somewhat ad
hoc (each action will have its own protocol).  We haven't even discussed
lots of these things, such as symbol change, continuity assign, etc.

This protocol for the entire "gmove family" will be somewhat similar. 
Leftclick on any POINT and then leftclick again to set the point's
destination at the current cursor location.  To set a fixed point, just
doubleclick on a point.  A line (or dot in case of fixed point) will
appear to describe the entered data, but no men will yet be moved.  When a
sufficient amount of information has been entered, the action will execute.

If you select an icon and execute an action, the icon remains "current." 
The current icon will affect the way that some things work.  For example,
if any of the gmove family is current, then leftclick is used
for individual move.  However, if label flip is current, then leftclick
will flip a label.  We have yet to work out the full details of this. 
There is a "nullmove" icon that can be selected in case something like
label flip is current, but you want leftclick to be used for individual move.

Underlying all of this structure are the obvious things like abort, undo
last command, redo last action, select all, select none, etc.

--------

That's the end of my formal explanation.  Now for more informal
discussion.  The more I think about it, the more I am convinced that what
I have described above is the way to go.  Note that the set of visible
icons can change, dependent on which icon is current.  Of course, some
things should always be visible, such as nullmove (I imagine that we will
find a need for other null actions, such as nullrefpoint or
nullsymbolchange), so that the informal concept of mode can be changed. 
However, EVERYTHING can always be accessed by using menus, no matter which
icons are actually visible.  Some commands won't make sense unless certain
icons are current - for example, zap won't do anything unless one of the
refpoint-related icons is current. 

The idea here is that there is no need for a formal definition of mode. 
The state of the interface is determined by the general type of the most
recent action.  If you last did a rotation, that's move mode.  If you last
changed a plainman to a solidbackslashman, that's symbol mode.

> 
> Yeah, you don't need to point that out.  Well, off to concert band.

Last night while lying in bed (that's where I do most of my thinking about
calchart), I came up with a great idea for a brand new feature.  Recall
the meaning of NP (nextpos) in continuity language.  We should install PP
(prevpos) in the obvious way - I've definitely had a use for it in the past.

That's a good idea, but it's not quite the great idea I had.  The great
idea occurred when I noticed the similarity in the way that NP and R1 are
treated by the continuity language.  In some sense, NP is the "zeroth
reference point."  We should install a feature that shows the next
stuntsheet or the previous stuntsheet in purple concurrently with the current
stuntsheet.  This would be a huge help to people designing shows right at
the console, and even more help to people trying to fix collisions and
making small changes like switching two men.  Hell, why not allow ANY
other stuntsheet to be superimposed?

Moreover, we should just allow simultaneous display of another sheet. 
Normally, even when another sheet is superimposed, all actions are applied
ONLY to men on the current sheet.  However, if the user prespecifies, all
subsequent actions will be applied to the OTHER sheet.  This works in
the same way that refmode currently works in the old version.

There is a small amount of danger in that this feature is very powerful,
and users can accidentally make edits to other sheets without realizing
it.  So, the request that changes occur on the OTHER sheet should probably
NOT be accessible by an icon - it would be too easy to accidentally click
on it and then get into trouble REAL fast.  Also, we should restrict the
allowable actions only to move-related actions.  You can move points if
you want, but you can't change symbols or redefine continuity.

The purpose for this feature is to prevent the necessity of switching back
and forth between two stuntsheets every 15 seconds while edits are being made.

Dan


