> 
> Okay, this should help clarify some things.

Based on your responses below, I can tell that we are converging to the
same mental picture.  However, we're not quite there yet.  I'll try to
clarify some more.
 
> 
> I believe you're referring to XOR?  I always thought that a NOT operates
> on only one operand.  Anyway, something that many interfaces use is that 
> if you have a group of objects, selecting something else will deselect 
> the first group.  But you can hold down a key, such as shift, and the 
> selections are ORed together.  I believe this may be the way to go, since 
> it's used in many interfaces.  Of course, XORing the selections might 
> help so you don't have to start over when you make a mistake, but might 
> not be as intuitive.

Well, it's a NOT or an XOR, depending on how you look at it.  I was
thinking of the first selection as establishing truth and falsity for each
point.  Then the values within the second selection would be NOTed.  On
the other hand, you can think of both the first and second selection as
inputs for the XOR.  Anyway, it's the same thing.

There should definitely be a way to subtract points from a selection. 
Too many points are accidentally selected as often as too few are.  ORing will
not provide this capability.  Maybe hold one key for adding points (OR)
and another for removing ({first} AND NOT{second}).
 
> 
> I think you should be able to change this information as much as you want 
> and then hit return when you like it.

OK.  That's possible.  But we're going to have to deal with the fact that
once the action is determined uniquely, you can't add new information in
any arbitrary fashion.  We'll have to work out some way of "editing" the
data describing the action.  In some cases, this will be easy.  for
example, if you incorrectly set the center of a rotation, just reclick on
the new center.  But the actions that require more than one piece of
information or variable amounts of information will be more tricky.
 
> Here's a problem.  How do you separate selection and the actions.  An 
> action could be executed by a click on a MAN, and clicks on other points 
> could be for selections.  This would be limiting in some respects, but 
> this is a limition of the current version.  Other options: must deselect 
> men before reselecting, different modes for selecting points and actions, 
> must click on icon first for special action.  Ideas?

Here is one of the issues that I did not make clear to you.  Selection is
what happens under the "normal" state of affairs.  However, once you click
on an icon, the program immediately expects action data, not selection
data.  Let's say you want to do a rotation.  FIRST select all the points
that will be rotated.  Get the set of points exactly right.  THEN click on
the rotation icon.  Now the program expects the next click to be the
center of rotation.  So, there's no ambiguity - the program knows from
context whether the information is to be used to define the action or to
select points.

Even if the desired icon is current, you STILL have to click on it if you
want to execute the same action again.
 
> 
> I'm not quite sure what you mean by "nullmove" but let me see if I've got 
> this right.  The basic move mode can be used for everything, e.g. you can 
> select some men, pick their new symbol from a menu and they'll be 
> changed.  They are other modes, however, that are more like the current 
> calchart where you can pick a symbol and then click on men or drag a 
> selection and they'll be changed automatically.  This could make some 
> actions a lot quicker.  Maybe we can follow the analogy of a paint 
> program, where there are different "tools" that can be used to "paint" 
> the men.  The move mode would be more like a CAD program where the men 
> are treated as separate objects.  One thing that's generally accepted 
> about user interfaces is that making it mode-based can end up confusing 
> the user.  So following some sort of analogy would be good.  But maybe it 
> would be better to make the right button action change instead of the 
> entire interface.  So you could still select men, but if you right 
> click on them, the symbol will change.

Here is the idea I have in mind.  Leftclick and rightclick are the two
easiest forms of input for human bodies.  Thus, we should try to make
these two things as useful as possible.  If I'm setting lots of symbols, I
don't give a fuck that smartmove can be executed at a moment's notice by
pressing the right mouse button.  In that sense, it's a "waste of
convenience" to have rightclick ALWAYS mean smartmove.

How can the program guess what meaning for rightclick would be most
convenient for the user?  Of course it can't always tell, but it can make
a good guess based on the most recently executed action.  If the last
action was changing a block of symbols, then it seems pretty likely that
the next command will also be symbolchange.  It doesn't HAVE to be this
way, but symbolchange is the most likely of all the possibilities. 
Therefore, immediately after a symbolchange, rightclick should cause a
symbolchange for the man at the cursor location.  To symbolchange a
selected set, the user would still have to click on the symbolchange icon
(or on the repeat-last-action icon).
 
Sometimes the program will guess wrong.  It will suspect that another
symbolchange is coming, but in fact smartmove really is the next thing I
want to do.  How can I reestablish the meaning of rightclick to be
smartmove?  I would have to perform a move-related action, and then the
program would change the meaning of rightclick to be smartmove.  But I
don't want to do anything except for smartmove.  So I can click on the
nullmove icon, which is move-related but doesn't cause any changes in the
location of men.

> 
> Okay, rather than what I said above, something like this.  If you've 
> selected a transformation, a right click will do smart move.  If men are 
> selected, a right click will put you in a special mode where you can 
> specify the needed info and you can hit return to do the transformation.  
> If you've selected a symbol or similar action, a right click will set the 
> symbol.  If you select men, no more information is need, so hitting 
> return will set the symbol (this way you can select multiple regions 
> before setting the symbol).  This actually sounds like it might be 
> similar to what you are saying.  I think something like this would 
> definately be easier to use than to make completely different modes.  I 
> still don't understand this "nullmove" thing.  Maybe a mode that has 
> smart move, but when you try to do a transformation, a popup window asks 
> you for the transformation type?  Similar mode for setting symbols?  I'm 
> not sure how useful this would be, if that's what you mean.

I'll try to clarify my meaning sentence by sentence.  If I've just
clicked on a transformation icon, all I can do is enter data to define the
transformation (or abort).  However, if a transformation icon is current
(i.e., the most recent action) then rightclick means smartmove.

If men are selected, then I'm not sure what rightclick should mean.  Maybe
it shouldn't mean anything since the purpose of selecting men is to choose
an action by clicking on an icon.  I think that a special meaning under
this special circumstance would be confusing.

If symbolchange is the current icon (ie, most recently executed action),
then rightclick will be individualsymbolchange.  If labelflip is the
current icon, then rightclick is individuallabelflip.

After you select men, you must ALWAYS specify the action by clicking on
the desired icon (or using the menu or keyboard) or by choosing a special
command such as repeat-last-action.  If you want to symbolchange different
blocks simultaneously, FIRST select ALL of them, then click on the
appropriate icon.

Notice that I've only talked about rightclick having a varying purpose.  I
think that it is a good idea to leave leftclick set on individualmove. 
First of all, individualmove is so useful so often.  Second, smartmove is
obscure enough to start with that people will not be terribly confused if
their right button keeps changing purpose.  Also, notice that I am always
distinguishing between leftclick and leftdrag, as in the old version.

> 
> You can move men while viewing the refpoints in the old version?

I didn't mean EXACTLY the same way.  I meant that the concept of
overlaying other sets of points in purple (or some other color), while
only the "topmost" layer could actually be changed.
 
> 
> I agree that this would be very useful.  To apply another analogy, call 
> this feature "onion skin".  This is used in paint programs for viewing 
> multiple frames of an animation at the same time.  Its name comes from 
> tradition animation where artists use "onion skin" paper (looks like onion 
> skin, but it isn't really) which is partially transparent in order see 
> one frame while drawing another.  Anyway, there'd be menu selections to 
> bring up next, previous, or any arbitrary stuntsheet behind the current 
> one.  I think maybe you should only be able edit the topmost one, with an 
> easy way to swap the two, so the bottom one is on top, and you can edit 
> that one.

You've got the idea on this.  I'll trust your opinion on the best method
of implementation since you've seen this kind of thing before.  You are
certainly correct that only the topmost sheet should be editable - WAY too
confusing any other way.
 
> By the way, I'm taking a grad class in math this semester.  Math 275, a 
> seminar on game theory, taught by Prof. Berlekamp, who is one of the top 
> three game theorists in the world.  It was recommended to me by my CS TA 
> last semester.  It's been pretty good so far.

I've never studied much game theory formally, but there was a little of it
in Econ 103 (mathematical economics).  I really liked the course.  It is
taught by Debreu, who is a nobel laureate in econ, and the only
prerequisite is math 50AB (no econ requirement at all).

