> 
> As far as different colors for source and destination endpoints, I think 
> it might be nice to put a purple "refpoint" at the destination endpoint 
> and nothing at the source.  About editing the data, I hadn't thought 
> about being able to edit the source endpoints, but this might be 
> helpful.  My question is what would the left button do?  Since it 
> normally moves single points, it seems that it should move an endpoint, 
> and maybe the right button can clear an entry.  Or would the left button 
> exit and go into block move?  I think the first would be better.

I like the idea of having a dot at the source end and just the end of the
line at the origin.  This will make the display of fixed points nice.  It
will look like a source endpoint without any line attached.

Remember that the left button is to be used for creating NEW data.  so it
can't also mean move an endpoint, unless the maximum amount of data has
already been entered.  I suppose leftclick could be for new data, and left
drag for altering old data.
 
What do you mean by "exit and go into block move?"  I'm not sure what
"block move" is.  Maybe you mean that the action should be aborted.  In
that case, the program would return to the state where the original
selected set is still selected, and it is waiting either for an alteration
to the selected set or the choice of some action.  Maybe you mean "block
move" in the old version sense.  But we've done away with block move and
replaced it with the translation action, which is a member of the g-move
family.

> 
> Oh, so there is a "set symbol mode" and then another menu of icons to 
> pick the symbol.  Yes, this is definately better.

Well, I don't want to think of it as a separate mode.  Think of it as
analogous to the situation with the g-move family.  After choosing an
action, the user has to give more information (lines with endpoints,
etc.).  Similarly, when change symbol is chosen, more information must be
given.  In particular, the user must specify to WHICH symbol should the
selected set be changed.  So a little window with eight icons pops up, and
the user clicks on one.

I like the idea trying to make the implementation of all actions somewhat
uniform.  The basic structure is: first select some points; second choose
an action; third give more information to define the action precisely.

For example, change-continuity-assignment should work as follows.  choose
your set of points.  then click on the change-cont-assignment icon.  Then
a list of all continuities appears.  click on the desired continuity.  The
default value would be whichever continuity group was most recently used
for any purpose.
 
> 
> Hopefully some things can be tucked away in menus.

I think we'll be able to manage somehow.  for example, we could put all of
the g-move family under a single icon.
 
> 
> Actually, it doesn't fully take advantage of X.  It's just some low-level 
> calls to make the DOS GUI work under X.  So just about any bug in the DOS 
> version should appear in the X version.

OK, whatever.  I don't know anything about this, and I don't fully
understand what you are saying.  so I'll take your word for it that my
testing will be useful.
 
> Well, I think this interface is reaching the end of the planning phase.  
> I can really think of anything more to say about it.  Time to start 
> coding I guess.  Anyway, thanks for your help!

Another random idea that came to me recently: alternate ways of selecting
points other than rectangular-select and lasso-select.  One should be able
to type a list of labels (with shorthand as in old program) to be
selected.  The most recently used list would remain a default value, so
that this feature could be very useful if for some reason the symbols of
men A1, B6, and T3 had to be changed on every single stuntsheet.

Also, one should be able to select points by specifying a symbol.  Choose
solidman, and all solidmen would be selected.  This has obvious uses,
especially for refpoints.  These two methods should be usable in
conjunction with each other and with rectangular-select and lasso-select.
That is, it should be possible to OR and XOR them in all possible ways.

I'm absolutely certain that when you get down to details, you'll discover
that we forgot lots and lots of things.  It is impossible to think of
everything ahead of time when you are dealing with a program as
complicated as this.

Does Microsoft have a position for full-time interface designer?  I think
I'd like that job.

