> 
> Yeah, I like the sound of this.  There should definately be a key defined 
> to bring up this window though.

And this concept will work for other modes.  If you want to type in new
continuity, select the editcont icon, then choose the group from a list. 
Then a text window appears.

If you want to flip labels, select the label icon, then choose flip,
right, or left.  As always, the most recent is the default.
 
> 
> This could be very useful.  One thing I had been thinking about that I 
> forgot to mention is having the selected points appear in a different color
> in the animation.  This way, for pregame or whatever, you can see where 
> all the basses are, or whatever.  You could also follow your own spot 
> pretty easily.  Maybe even be able to define groups.  So A0-9 are 
> percussion, or whatever.  Then you don't have to reselect these points 
> every time you want to know where the percussion is.

I like the idea of highlighting selected points in the animation.  I guess
we could work it the same way as always.  Click on the animate icon for
animation, but if you want to highlight some points, then FIRST select,
then click on animate.

I wouldn't bother with prespecifying the percussion spots.  It's not going
to be used very often, and it just feels kind of cumbersome and unnatural. 
On the other hand, maybe we should install it, just in case someone
decides several years from now that they really want it.  OK, I've
convinced myself now that it is a good idea.

The names of groups of points should be text, as for continuity
assignments.  One can select points by asking for a group name.  To change
group definitions, select points and then use an appropriate action.  It
is possible for one man to lie in more than one group.

There should be two kinds of groups - local and global.  Global groups
apply to every single stuntsheet - change it's definition on one sheet,
and you change it on every sheet simultaneously.  This is useful for
things like studying the percussion line or the basses in pregame.

Local groups only apply to a particular stuntsheet.  They have no bearing
on other sheets, and probably there don't even exist groups on other
sheets with the same name.  Even if there is another local group on
another sheet with the same name, the two groups are completely indepedent.

What about groups that exist on more than one stuntsheet but not all?  Forget
it - just use a global group and ignore it where you don't want it.

Oh, this is getting better and better.  Notice that the notion of symbol
is really just a special type of local group - one that happens to affect
the printout.  Note that continuity assignments are also just local groups
- they happen to affect animation.  Even labels are singleton global
groups.  I really really really like the idea that we have generalized
several seemingly distinct concepts into one unifying idea!  I don't know
much about coding, but I suspect that this concept will be useful for you
in writing the program.

What about the idea of applying actions to global groups with the intent
of applying that action on every stuntsheet?  I'm a little wary of this
because a user could really fuck things up in a hurry by misusing this
tool.  On the other hand, relabeling a show is really an action on the
global groups defined by label.  Some commands would be more useful than
others.  For example, symbol would probably be used, but movement actions
would not likely be useful.  Who cares?  There's nothing wrong with
implementing options that are even more powerful than necessary. 

Allowing global actions is going to mean that sometimes there will be a
use for groups that are defined on more than one sheet but not all.  So,
we'll need some way to create such things - shouldn't be too hard.

Now, I have a whole new way of thinking about symbol, continuity, labels,
etc.  I have a feeling that after I think through this, I'm going to have
some new ideas on things like labels that change during a show, autocont,
and so forth.

I realize that most of the stuff I'm talking about has little or no use. 
But the point of the new version is to make things more powerful, so why
not install it?  Can you imagine trying to explain this to stunt?  They'll
NEVER understand it.  See what a casual little comment by one person can
inspire another to do?

> 
> Well, I've still got another year here.  Hopefully, this project can be 
> improved apon after I graduate.  I've been trying to comment my code 
> really well (which is hard considering that I rarely use comments).  One 
> of the reasons calchart has changed very little since Martin graduated is 
> that there are NO comments.  I had to go through the source to figure out 
> the file format, and to fix a couple bugs, and it took a long time.

You know what the really cool thing about having you work on the new
version is?  You are also a mello.  You, Martin, and I are all mellos. 
Mellos OWN calchart.
 
> Which reminds me... I discovered that there is an older file format that 
> calchart supports, presumably from version 1?  I never really bothered to 
> figure out this format, and I'm wondering if I need to support it.  I 
> looked through the old archives from '90 and they all seem to be in the 
> new format.  Do you know anything about this?  From what I've seen they 
> aren't very different, so I'm also wondering why the switch?

I'm not sure about the old file format, but I seem to remember something
about it.  The very first Calchart show was pregame 90, so if it works for
that show, then it should work on anything.
 
> Also, certain features could be abused.  For instance, I considered 
> putting in an option to rate the difficulty of shows or flows (something 
> like the readability feature in word processors) but I realized that this 
> is a very bad idea.  Stunt might decide to cut out a certain flow because 
> calchart says it's above-average difficulty for a one week show.  Or they 
> might base their decision for student charting in part on the difficulty 
> rating calchart gives.  I guess I don't really have a point except that 
> I'm afraid of giving too much power to the user and allowing to not look 
> at how the flows work.

Oh, this is a very very BAD BAD idea.  Don't even TELL stunt about this
because they will probably think it is cool.  The influence of calchart on
our marching style is bad enough - this would blatantly exacerbate the
situation.  I mean, if we keep going the way we are, we'll end up with a
program that WRITES the shows.  The one advantage of this is that stunt
could then be disbanded.  It's ok to allow some aspects to remain under
human control.
 
> 
> I believe they do.  Probably called a "design engineer" or something like 
> that.  I went to a presentation on campus that they made last year, and I 
> seem to recall something like this.

actually, i'm probably not qualified for them.  you probably have to have
a lot of programming experience so that you can understand how hard it
would be to actually implement ideas.


I've changed my mind about the whole rightclick controversy that we went
through last week.  We had finally decided that there should be a way to
redefine the meaning of rightclick, completely independently of everything
else that is going on.  I've decided that this is just not worth it. 
Instead, rightclick should ALWAYS mean individual-select.  It would be
exactly the same as making a very small rectangle about one man, EXCEPT
that if points are already selected, then rightclicking will NOT kill the
old selection - instead, it will XOR.  This way, you could rightclick two
men consecutively, and both would then be highlighted.  This situation is
nearly as good as being able to redefine the meaning of rightclick. 
Instead specifying the meaning and THEN rightclicking on men, you now have
to rightclick on men and THEN specify the action.

This still leaves the question of how to deal with smartmove.  Like
individualmove, smartmove should be considered as a bit of an exception to
the normal structure of actions.  First, individually move two points with
leftclick.  Then, click on the smartmove icon.  From now on, ALL clicks
(both left and right) will execute smartmoves.  This situation will last
until it is actively aborted by the user (hit ESC, I guess).

How about left click for the original smartmove, and rightclick for
"negative smartmove."  The point jumps into line, but it gets added on the
"negative" end of the line, not the positive end.  I honestly can't think
of a good use for this, but what the hell?  I guess that's easy for me to
say - I don't have to write the code.  :)

Now I'm trying to think of a way to implement a twodimensional smartmove. 
This could be very useful.  I'll have to spend some time pondering this.

Dan


