> 
> If you've selected a bunch of points, and then left click on one, you go 
> into the translation mode, right?  I was just saying that this would 
> always be true, even if you were entering data for, say genius move.  But 
> it doesn't matter.  This idea was lame to begin with.

As I understood it, if you select some points and then leftclick on one,
it won't do anything.  In order to get a translation, you have to click
the translate icon, then input one movement vector.
 
> 
> Well, you could set one to some arbitrary location, then set the other 
> one to the correct location, then move then first to the correct 
> location.  Here's a possible idea.  Left click will enter new data.  
> Right click can modify existing data.  While editing it, you can hit 
> 'DEL' or something like that to clear it (or maybe 'ESC').  This could 
> also be used to back out of entering a new piece of data.

I don't understand your explanation at the beginning of the paragraph.  If
the two lines are identical, how can you move one without moving the other
in a natural way?  Clicking in ANY location will not distinguish between
the two overlapping lines.

I think it is more logical to have left for new data, and right for
editing existing data.  And delete or escape as you suggest for removing data.
However, we STILL have to deal with the potential problem of overlapping
endpoints.
 
> 
> Yes, I forgot about the point for rotation.  What about reflections?  We 
> agreed to limit it to N/S, E/W, NW/SE, NE/SW so a point should be 
> enough.  Here's an idea.  You define one movement for the reflection 
> line, and it will snap to one of these directions.

It's true that we agreed to limit the possible directions of reflection
lines.  However, it is not always natural to define a reflection by
clicking on the fixed line.  If you want to reflect a box about the line
passing down its middle, then it's easy to click on the fixed line.  But
let's say that a block is going to reflect and end up 20 yards south. 
Then the fixed line would lie somewhere in between the original location
of the block and the final destination.  You would have to mentally
calculate the distance, then divide by two, blah, blah to find the fixed
line.  Much easier to just move one man.

So, we should allow EITHER definition: (double) click on the fixed line OR
move one man.  This means that we cannot allow the direction of reflection
to be defined by the direction of movement, because if you want to define
a point on the fixed lie, then there is no implicit direction.  I think
that the best solution is to prespecify the direction of the axis.  If
the user specifies a movement, it will snap to the only possible direction
of motion (perpendicular to reflection line).
 
> 
> I think the best thing to do is have a line of text at the bottom of the 
> screen for messages.  So when you enter a mode it will say, "Please enter 
> three points" or whatever.  It could also say, "Vectors must be parallel" 
> or "Tranformation is now defined".

Sure, this makes sense.  I wasn't really making an observation on the
interface.  This had more to do with the fact that the routine would have
to have some internal error-checking.



I've been thinking about the 2dimensional smartmove.  One problem that i
have is that I can't think of a good way to make it a strict
generalization of original smartmove.  By this, I mean that I can't design
it in such a way that 1dimensional smartmove is still just as easy to use
as the oldfashioned smartmove.  So, it would have to be implemented as a
separate feature: say, "clevermove."

Here is my idea for clevermove.  Maybe you will have a good idea to
improve it.  The input is destinations p1, p2, and p3 of the three most
recent individualmoves (analogously, smartmove has inputs destinations p1
and p2 of the two most recent individualmoves).  Think of p1 as the base
point; in actual application, it would be the SE corner of a block. Also,
p2 is the man next to p1 on the east face of the block, and p3 is the man
behind p1 on the south face of the block.

Set v2 = p2 - p1, and v3 = p3 - p1.  So v2 represents the NS spacing, and
v3 represents the EW spacing.  When you invoke clevermove, a cursor
appears at p1 + 2 v2 (just to the north of p2).  Whenever you rightclick
on a point, it is immediately moved into the position occupied by the
cursor.  Simultaneously, the cursor automatically increments by v2 (moves
another 2 steps to the north).  In fact, this might be a really nice
graphical way of dealing with smartmove - it would make it easier to
remember what's going on.

Now, the cursor can be moved outside of its automatic increment.  Press
the right arrow key, and the cursor location is incremented by v2.  Press
the left arrow key, and the cursor location is incremented by -v2.  Use up
arrow key for incrementing by v3, and down arrow for incrementing by -v3.

Using the arrow keys, it would be really easy to move around a block.  One
problem is that the user might have to keep going back and forth between
arrows and mouse.  so maybe we should use the A,S,W,Z keys in addition to
arrows so that the user could press keys with his left hand and use the
mouse with his right.

There should also be a special key that would send the cursor to position p1 +
(n+1) v3 whenever the cursor is currently at position p1 + m v2 + n v3. 
In application, this means that if you are currently working on the third
NS line, you can easily jump to the south end of the fourth NS line.  Sort
of like a typewriter's carriage return.

I know it's not perfect.  Maybe it's so cumbersome that it's not even
worth implementing.  What do you think?  At the very least, it's got a
good name.  "Clever" is more than "smart" but less than "genius."

Dan




From dci@math.uchicago.edu Fri Feb  3 13:51:39 1995
Received: from dent.uchicago.edu (dent.uchicago.edu [128.135.72.13]) by pasteur.EECS.Berkeley.EDU (8.6.9/8.6.4) with ESMTP id NAA07701 for <gmeeker@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU>; Fri, 3 Feb 1995 13:51:35 -0800
Received: (dci@localhost) by dent.uchicago.edu (8.6.9/8.6.5) id PAA20142 for gmeeker@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU; Fri, 3 Feb 1995 15:51:31 -0600
From: Dan Isaksen <dci@math.uchicago.edu>
