> 
> Yes.  The "Grand Unified Theory of CalChart!"

I'm going to write a separate letter about the GUT.
 
> 
> The CS term for it is scope.  Basically a local group definition 
> overrides a global group definition.  So you can define a global group 
> called "A POINTS" containing A0-9.  Then on stuntsheet 13 define a local 
> group with the same name containing A1-9.  Then if you select "A POINTS" 
> on stuntsheet 13 you get A1-9, but on all others you get A0-9.

I just realized that your "masking" and my ideas are really the same.  It
had occurred to me that there really is no such thing as a local group
since any group that only appears on one stuntsheet can be thought of as a
global group that happens to equal the empty set on all other sheets.  So,
"A POINTS" is really only one group, where the men in the group might vary
from sheet to sheet. 
 
> 
> Okay this is pretty cool theoretically, but will leave the user baffled.  
> What I propose is the ability to define a group of groups to be mutually 
> exclusive.  I'm not sure offhand the best way to do this, but for 
> instance the symbol groups are mutually exclusive.  You could also define 
> groups for the different instruments, which of course would be mutually 
> exclusive.  Oh, maybe you could even define a group to be a superset of 
> several groups, so you could define a "brass" group or whatever.  I was 
> going to suggest something else, but I just had a new idea.  I like the 
> idea of assigning continuity to a group, though.  Actually that might 
> even be easier for the user.  Maybe the program can just give an error if 
> a man has continuity from several groups.  The built-in groups are 
> exceptions, so a plainman can have use continuity from a different 
> group.  Anyway usually groups will be created specifically for continuity 
> and these can be set to be mutually exclusive.

I think you figured out what I was saying halfway through your paragraph. 
We really aren't changing the WAY continuity is assigned, we are just
changing our viewpoint of it.

I'll address mutual exclusivity in the GUT.
 
> 
> This is getting pretty wild.  The interface to this might be tricky.

Just to warn you, I think it's going to get even wilder.  I don't think
that the interface is a big concern on this issue.  It's not like these
things are particularly useful.  I'm more concerned over the question of
whether they should be POSSIBLE or not.
 
> 
> Well, I don't know the exact mathematics offhand, but usually curves are 
> done with quadratic splines and if the endpoints and control points of 
> two curves match up, you get a smooth curve.  I guess it makes the first 
> derivative of the curves continous.  I guess one way to implement it is 
> start out with an open or closed segment.  Then the user can add or 
> remove segment points along this path.  Moving the points changes the 
> curve.  Actually there are certain programs (like 3D rendering types) 
> that do something similar for animation of objects (or for moving the 
> camera in an animation).

Ugh!  Splines are really rather messy.  I guess it wouldn't be too bad if
the user clicked on some points to define a spline.  There would have to
be a way to go back and add points in the middle of the spline to make it
more accurate if necessary.  This makes the interface a bit tricky.  

After the spline is defined, the user would specify the number of men to
be placed along the curve.  The program would calculate arc lengths to
figure out where the men should be placed along the curves.

This kind of thing is done in the published corps-style charting software.
I wonder if we could get our hands on a copy and see how others have
solved the problem.  Again, this idea belongs on the back burner, so
there's no practical hurry to decide.  However, I like discussing anything
and everything under the sun.  It never hurts to think about things ahead
of time.
 
> Something along the same lines: how do you animate the script cal flow?  
> This isn't that big of a deal, but maybe you can define a curve to travel 
> along.

Martin and I considered this the holy grail of calchart programmers.  We
did come up with a pretty good solution, but we never bothered to
implement it because it was generally only used once a year for script cal.

The idea was to define a FTL continuity command.  Each man would be
assigned a "predecessor."  The man's continuity would be defined by DTP to
the originating location of the predecessor, then execute the
predecessor's continuity until the man reaches his own new spot.

This construction gives a recursively defined flow, but there is still the
problem of defining the line leader's continuity (the base case of the
recursion).  We didn't have a good idea for this, other than using MARCH
for straight segments and ROTATE for arcwise approximating curved paths.

Dan



From dci@math.uchicago.edu Tue Feb  7 18:18:43 1995
Received: from uclink.berkeley.edu (uclink.Berkeley.EDU [128.32.155.3]) by pasteur.EECS.Berkeley.EDU (8.6.9/8.6.4) with ESMTP id SAA10084 for <gmeeker@pasteur.eecs.berkeley.edu>; Tue, 7 Feb 1995 18:18:38 -0800
