[Al: This is the result of discussions between Gurk and me about the new
version of Calchart.  I wrote it for him, so you might not understand the
context.  But I thought you would enjoy it anyway.]

I don't really like the name "Grand Unified Theory."  Any suggestions?

Dan
--------------------

First I'll present some set theoretic preliminaries.

The power set of S is the collection of all subsets of S.  An atom is an
object which is NOT a set itself.  They are the "indivisible" elements of
whatever universe is under consideration.  A collection of sets is
finitely generated if the collection consists of sets of sets of sets ....
of sets of finitely many different atoms.

Axiom 1:  The atoms are the elements of R^2 x Z.

Axiom 1 is based on the assumption that the band essentially exists only
on the football field, and the field is clearly closely modelled by R^2
with rectangular coordinates.  Of course there are exceptions, such as
coming out of the stands, parachuting, and trap doors in the astroturf. 
However, the exceptions are unlikely enough for us to eliminate them from
consideration.

The factor of Z (the set of integers) allows for the possibility that finitely
many men may be at the same point on the field (e.g., shoulder pass).

Axiom 2:  Everything is discrete and finite.

Axiom 2 is based on the idea that the band consists of a finite number of
individual members.  Hence, the state of the marching band at any given
time can be described by a finite set of points on the field.

There is an important exception to this.  Although the band consists of
individual members, these points on the field are often meant to emulate a
continuous object such as a curve or a solid box.  For this reason,
corps-style programs generally have provisions for things like splines. 
Regardless, we're going to ignore this for now in order to be able to
actually draw some conclusions.

Theorem 1: Any show can be encoded as a finitely generated subcollection of
the power set of R^2.

Proof: Shows have a finite number of beats, and there are a finite number
of bandsmen.  So the collection of all points on the field occupied by any
bandsman at any time during the show is finite.  All other points are
irrelevant, so the subcollection, if it exists, is finitely generated by
this "totality of locations."

The state of any bandsman on a given stuntsheet can be described by some
pieces of information (label, symbol, continuity, position, associated
refpoints, etc.).  For each stuntsheet t and value of "information" I, define
S(t, I) = {pts on the field occupied on stuntsheet t by men possessing
"information" I on stuntsheet t}.  For example, S(16, SOLBKSL) = the set of
points p, which on ss 16 have a solid-back-slashman located at p.

Then the collection of S(t, I), where t and I run through all possible
values, is the desired subcollection. [endproof]

I do have a small concern about this kind of analysis.  Reducing things to
set theoretic concepts can result in a loss of useful algebraic structure.
The "forgetful functor" is the function that sends any object to it's
underlying set.  It is called forgetful because a lot of information is
lost in the transfer.  Here we aren't losing information because we are
NOT merely mapping to the underlying subset of R^2 x Z, but we may be
obscuring a potentially powerful algebraic point of view.  However, I
have not yet discovered such an algebraic point of view, so this is the
best model we have so far.

----------------

That's about all I have to say about formal theory.  Now the question is
what this really means in our practical situation.  The fundamental issue
is:  What is the most logical and useful way to store, present, and
manipulate the sets that define a show?  I leave the question of how the
program internally stores data to the programmers, who know much more
about this issue than I do.

In a limited sense, this set theoretic viewpoint really is useful.  In an
informal sense, shows are about different bandsmen doing different
things.  If not for this difference, then shows would just be a single block
moving around the field without changing shape.  For ease of comprehension
for the human mind, it is nice to group bandsmen into sections that are
doing the same thing at a particular time.  The memberships of these sets
changes over time - otherwise, a show would just be several different
blocks moving around the field without changing shape.  From this
perspective, it is clear how the set theory can be a useful construction.

I think we've already worked out most of the details of our interface.  We
know from several years of experience what kinds of things are useful,
what features are commonly used, what features are used but infrequently,
etc.  I'm planning on eventually getting around to writing down a list of
all the ideas that we've had so far.

---------------

After all considerations of user interface are answered, we are still left
with the fact that the program is doing nothing more than manipulating
sets.  Therefore, a "set theory menu" [I need a better name.  Any
suggestions?] that allows for ARBITRARY manipulation of sets will
necessarily provide the capability of doing absolutely anything that
exists under axioms 1 and 2.  By arbitrary manipulation, I mean that at
any time, a set with any given name containing any finite subset of R^2 x
Z can be created; and any existing set can be erased or edited to consist
of any finite subset of R^2 x Z; and the name of any set can be changed to
any other name. 

The manipulations provided on the set theory menu do not necessarily
have to be handy or intuitive.  The point here is the simple EXISTENCE of
the ability to do something, not the ease with which it is done.  All
questions of easiness should be addressed with the regular user interface.
The set theory menu is meant to be never actually used or used only
under the most bizarre of situations.

It will be a good idea to include many of the common set theoretic
operations and relationships on the set theory menu.  I have in mind such
operations as union, intersection, complement, symmetric difference (XOR),
possibly even power set.  Also, it would be convenient to define
relationships between different sets which cannot be broken unless the
user cancels the relationship.  For example, mutual exclusivity,
inclusion, or covering (require that the union of sets U1, ..., Un
contains set U).

Here is an example of a "bizarre" situation in which the set theory menu
could come in handy:  the show starts with half the bandsmen standing on
the shoulders of the other half - so there are only 72 men on each
stuntsheet.  12 stuntsheets later, the bandsmen on top jump off and start
marching on their own.  The animation of stuntsheet 13 to stuntsheet 14
calls for 72 points to become 144 points - each point "doubles."

Using the set theory menu, the user would be able to define the
"animation correspondence" sets (i.e., man at point (x,y) on SS9 marches
to point (w,z) on SS10) in such a way that each source (men on SS13) has
two destinations (men on SS14).  Then, the program would properly animate
the flow.

Note that I am NOT implying that this capability is actually useful.  I'm
just mentioning that it could conceivably be used by someone.

This complete freedom in defining sets will sometimes confuse the program.
It generally assumes that an animation correspondence set of point (x,y)
consists of a single point on the succeeding stuntsheet.  In the above
example, this is not the case.  Also, it generally assumes that each point
lies in exactly one continuity set.  In order to deal with these bizarre
situations, some conventions will have to be established.  For example,
continuity should probably be concatenated in some arbitrary order.





