> 
> Looking forward to seeing it.

I've run into a few problems while writing.  First, I don't think our idea
for the translation shortcut will work.  We had the idea that left
dragging immediately after defining a selected set would execute a
translation.  But left draggin immediately after selecting will cause
another rectangular selection.  So, I think we'll have to scrap the
shortcut idea.

Also, I am struggling over whether a group should be defined in terms of
points or in terms of men.  It might be nice to have groups where there
aren't men, but then what about when men are superimposed and you only want
some of the men to be assigned to the group?
 
> > Individualmove and refpoints are more of a problem because it is possible
> > to stack many many men on top of each other.  When you click on a
> > superimposed man, then you choose from a menu listing all the labels.  An
> > option to permit the program to choose one at random?
> 
> I like idea.  Of course "random" will actually be more like the 
> first man alphabetically (actually, the first man going by the table 
> of labels).  This would be the easiest algorithmically.  Maybe I didn't 
> explain that very well.  If the men are labeled A0-9, C0-9, B0-9 (or 
> maybe this will have to be alphabetic, I don't know) and B2, C2, and B7 
> are at the same point, C2 would be selected.

I meant "arbitrarily" when I typed "random."  But it does not make the
slightest difference how the arbitrary rule is defined.  Here is what I
envision the "arbitrary" feature to be used for.  Let's say you've got a
bunch of points all stacked on top of each other, but you want to move
them into some formation.  You're going to have to move them one at a
time, but you don't really care what order you do them in.  You don't want
to have to hassle with a submenu for every single move, so you can "turn
it off."

Come to think of it, this scenario is fairly unlikely.  Smartmove would
probably work quite well here as long as the formation has straight lines,
so you wouldn't want to work in a completely arbitrary order.  Maybe we
should not bother with the arbitrary option.  Somehow I don't like the
idea of a list of default values that can be changed.
 


