[Al: Thought you might like the "abstractness" of this discussion.]


Ok, I think I've FINALLY gotten it.  I was having trouble dealing with the
fact that labels consisted of one man from each stuntsheet.  This seemed to
make it impossible for stuntsheets and labels to be fundamentally the same
thing, and I couldn't figure out how to get around this problem.

Then I discovered the answer.  They are NOT the same.  The new construction
essentially belongs to "category theory," to put things in abstract
mathematical terms.  I am under the impression that intelligent languages
like C++ can deal quite nicely with these kinds of structures, but I'm not
at all sure of that.

Anyway, here's a description with concrete examples.  If you don't understand,
just ask for clarification.


A group is a set of points with multiplicity.  For example, stuntsheets and
reference point sheets are groups.  A subgroup is a subset of the set of
points.

A Group G is a collection of groups: one subgroup G(g) (possibly empty) for
each group g of the show.  For example, symbols are Groups, and so are labels.

A subGroup H of G is a Group such that for all g, H(g) is contained in G(g).
For example, "all solidmen on SS4-7" (call it H) is a subGroup of Solidman
since H(SSn) = Solidman(SSn) for n = 4,5,6,7, and H(g) = empty set for all
other groups.  In fact, H is a special kind of subGroup called a restriction
subGroup (my term, not mathematically standard).  A restriction subGroup H of
G is a subGroup such that for each g, H(g) = G(g) or H(g) = empty set.
Basically, H is the restriction of G to only SOME stuntsheets (groups).
Generally speaking, projection subGroups will be the most common type of
real application - this is the
analogous concept to our old idea of global and local groups.

A GGroup GG is a collection of Groups: for each Group G of the show,
GG(G) is a subGroup of G.  Here is an example of such a thing.  Suppose
that the band is split into four long lines, and each line is doing its own
follow-the-leader drill that extends for several stuntsheets.  Note that
the line leader is not necessarily the same for all sheets - the direction
of following could reverse, or the line could snake into a block and then
snake out of the block in a different way, etc.  There could even be more
than one line leader on any given SS.

The four lines make four separate Groups (A, B, C, D).  Note that they cannot
be realized as groups since they extend over several sheets.

Now A(SSn) is a group, and it has a (usually singleton, but not necessarily)
subgroup LineleaderA(SSn) consisting of the line-leader(s) for the flow of
line A on SSn.  So, LineleaderA is a subGroup of A.

Set LLineleader(A) = LineleaderA (and similarly for B, C, D).  Then 
LLineleader is a GGroup.  It consists of all of the lineleaders on all of the
stuntsheets.

One could also define Lineleader(SSn) to be all of the lineleaders of all
four lines on SSn.  Then Lineleader would be a Group, not a GGroup, and it
also consists of all of the lineleaders on all of the stuntsheets.  However,
there is a difference between Lineleader and LLineleader.  The difference
is that LLineleader remembers that certain lineleaders belong to the same
line, whereas Lineleader cannot distinguish between leaders of line B and
leaders of line A.

So, what's the point?  Let's say that A, B, C, and D are noted by the symbols
plain, X, slash, and bkslh respectively.  We want to mark all lineleaders 
with the corresponding solid symbol (solid, solidX, etc.).  This change could
be caused all at once with LLineleader.

Note that Lineleader would be sufficient if all we wanted to do was change
all lineleaders (regardless of which line) to solidmen, which is the way that
stuntsheets are usually done.




As another more abstract example, the collection of all restriction subGroups
of G is a GGroup GG:  GG(H) = H if H is a restriction subGroup of G, and
GG(H) = empty set otherwise.  

Speaking abstractly, we always assume that every possible group or Group or
GGroup does in fact exist.  However, this is obviously not the case in our
situation with a machine with finite amounts of memory.  So, the example
directly above gives the full collection of restriction subGroups in the
abstract sense, but in actuality, GG would only be the collection of those
restriction subGroups that actually had been already defined by the user.


Note that there is no reason to stop at the second level.  G^3roups are
perfectly well-defined, as are G^nroups for any positive integer n.  However,
as n increases, G^nroups are less and less likely to be actually useful.

Now I've got to adapt this abstract construction to our real problem.  I'll
keep you posted.


