I have been trying to deal with this problem by having reasonable default
values.  Initially, submenus only show the most likely choices, but more
choices can be added upon request.

> are displayed).  I guess there are really two distinctive kinds of 
> groups- those that have a fixed size with a one-to-one correspondance and 
> those that that are groups of groups (so the user can select which men 
> belong to the group, like plainmen).  Hmmm, I guess the actions taken by 
> the user on these two cases are quite different.

I think that you are essentially distinguishing between groups and Groups,
but I'm not sure.  The one-to-one correspondence that you are talking
about is really the labeling.  More generally, groups do not have to be
the same size; they are just arbitrary sets of points.  Label Groups set
up the correspondence between different sheets.

There really is a very common application of the ability to have groups of
different sizes.  Consider the tunnel flow and scriptcal flow sheets in 
pregame.  Currently we have to move the undesired points into the corner
and then use whiteout on the printed sheet.  With the new version, we
could just delete the undesired men from those stuntsheets - no problem at
all.
 
> Overall, this theoretical stuff is pretty cool, but I'm really starting 
> to wonder how in the HELL to put this in the program without utterly 
> confusing Stunt.

I am trying to write the interface so that it can be used by people with
different levels of understanding.  Essentially, the idea is that if you
haven't heard of a term or don't know about a feature, then just ignore
it.  Things like refpts can be done entirely with the group commands, but
there are also specific refpt commands that are basically redundant copies
of the corresponding group commands.  This way, people who understand
refpts but not groups can work easily.

I'm a little bit concerned that you haven't fully understood my
group/Group/GGroup ideas.  Maybe it's just that you haven't read those
letters yet.  Anyway, this concept is pretty fundamental to everything
that I'm doing now, so I'll reexplain it if necessary.

Sorry for overwhelming you with text.  Take your time with it; there's no
hurry.  After all, our agenda is entirely set by the rate at which you work.
Just because I don't have enough to do doesn't mean that you should have
to work faster.

Dan


