I'm going to retreat slightly from my completely abstract constructions. 
I fully realize that all that nonsense is not necessary or even desirable
in the actual program.  This is my opinion on what the program really should
do.

I've been having trouble making logical sense of many concepts without the
natural ordering of stuntsheets.  In particular, this is causing
difficulty with animation and with relabeling.  Anyway, I don't think that
animation can be described in any nice way strictly with unordered groups.

So, the concept of "ordering" becomes a fundamental idea - not just an
artificial construction for the convenience of the user.  This makes
fairly little difference in the actual coding, but it changes the way that
we as users should think about things and therefore will influence the
logic of the user interface.

However, it would be nice to bend the rules of strict linear animation
from time to time.  In particular, I'm thinking about flow sheets for a
complicated flow (e.g., script cal).  So, we allow for stuntsheets to be
"simultaneous" within the ordering of the show.  For example, sheets 12C,
12A, and 12L would all occur at the same time.  In real life, these sheets
DO occur at the same time - now the program will understand that idea. 
This seems like a good idea if for no other reason than that it reflects
reality.

This would not affect nextsheet or previoussheet; if you're on 12C and you
press N, you'll go to 12A, not 13.  I'm not certain yet how it would
affect relabeling - I'll have to think about that.  Basically, the only
difference it would really make is in animation.

--------------

On groups and Groups and GGroups.  Only groups and Groups have the
slightest chance of being useful, so lets throw away G^nroups for n
greater than or equal to 2.  For clarity of description, a Group from now
on will be called a "collection."  Now we won't have to depend on capital
letters; however, I will continue to use capital letters at the beginning
of the names of collections for clarity.  The term "collection" is
supposed to reflect the fact that it is a collection of subgroups.  

Dan


