> 
> Not quite.  For each point, it is defined on exactly one of the script 
> cal flow stuntsheets.  Since it is rather ineligant to just drag unused 
> points off into the corner, how do you move points between these three 
> shees?

Oh, I see what you are worrying about.  You are basically concerned about
what happens when there are stuntsheets with varying numbers of points.  I
haven't sent this to you yet, but I've designed a command that adds points
to groups, and another command that deletes points from groups.  In order
to move A4 from 12A to 12C, you'd have to delete it on 12A and add it on 12C.
Then, you'd have to assign it a label.  This is pretty cumbersome as it
stands, so maybe we'll make a shortcut if we think that this will be a fairly
common activity: something like "Movepoint."

Despite all of this, I think that there is a better way to deal with the
specific example of 12C, 12A, and 12L.  Define three separate collections
C, A, and L, where C(12) are the men in the Cflow, A(12) are the men in the
Aflow, and L(12) are the men in the Lflow.  Then it is easy to move A4
from one collection to another; just delete it from C(12) and add it to A(12).
I've already designed commands to allow for this kind of thing.

In order to print the separate flowsheets, we will enable the print routine
to print specific collections.  Actually, if you think about it, the print
routine already works this way.  It's just that there is no choice in the
collection - it is always Show.

By doing things in this way, I think that we will avoid just about all
circumstances when it will be necessary to move a man A4 from one
stuntsheet to another.
 
> 
> Maybe simultaneous isn't the best choice of wording.  You don't 
> necessarily have all continuity displayed at the same time.  Rather, 
> think of all of them appended into one file (so it's a little more like 
> the printed stuntsheets).  You can just move down and edit the apropriate 
> continuity.

OK, whatever you think is best.  The only that's really important to me is 
that we think of the text as being associated to the COLLECTION, not just the
stuntsheet.  This is quite important to the way that I would like to deal
with special continuity assignments.
 
> 
> Number keys are good.  Maybe +/- should speed up/slow down and have a key 
> to reverse directions?  Also the icons should be VCR style.  But maybe 
> you should be able to set the approxiate bpm for each stuntsheet so it's 
> somewhat syncronizied with the music.

Now we're getting somewhere!  All of your ideas sound good.  So, there are
two ways to view animation: manual and automatic.  For automatic, there
are three ways to adjust speed: keyboard (1-9, +, -), VCR style (icons and
scales), and bpm.  Even in automatic, it should be possible to jump around
to different stuntsheets.

Won't processors of varying power affect the bpm?  Or maybe you know how
to deal with that problem.  Come to think of it, I'm sure you do.  We're
not the first people ever to design a time-dependent application.

This afternoon I wrote an 8K document (160 lines) that I call the
"Calchart Version 3 Primer." It explains all of the new abstract concepts
in great detail with lots of examples.  I will send it to you, and I will
also send a copy to Erin.  The two of you should distribute it to a few
stuntmembers and other Calchart users (Hack, Trevor, Pearson).  It
is important to know whether anyone else will be able to understand our
ideas before we bother to write the program, and the only way we can find
out is by trying to explain it to someone else.  Please gather feedback
and let me know what the general opinion is.

Dan



