I'm not a computer programmer, but I remember you can make sub programms 
that can connect two things.  I'm pretty sure that's how the continuity 
is placed from the editor to the stuntsheets now I think.  If this is so 
you could write a subroutine that will look for key phrases in the old 
stuntsheets and equate it to print out something else.  Like for instance 
You could get the program to recognize EWNS TO NP
				       MTRM E   	in the calchart 
programm and then have it print out FMHS EW/NS TO S.S.$(this could be the 
stunt sheet name which is usually in sequential order) [MTHS E].  This 
could be defeating the purpose of having to enter continuity in one 
language.  But it would prevent us from typing two versions of the same 
continuity.  If we can link the two that way it would be easier.  Most of 
our continuity follows the same set of patterns. 
	step (x y rz) e --- typed out as:
			    Execute Step x as per arrows
			    Drill:
				continuity
			    [MTHS E BEFORE AND AFTER]

I think things like this could be recognized and translated by a 
subroutine of some sort.  I remember doing this in fortran and in pascal 
in high school.  these are pretty old programs now but I'm sure the newer 
ones can still do this if not better or quicker.



Neil


