Yeah, I should have known that no one else would really care.  The only
reason you care is that you are writing the program.  The only reason I
care is that I don't have a life in Chicago, so I have nothing better to
do with my free time than type detailed essays into the computer.

This is somewhat related to something that I wanted to tell you.  I made a
bad mistake during my time as Calchart guru.  I failed to inspire anyone
else to get involved.  Martin dragged me in, and I carried the torch for a
number of years.  Fortunately, you got involved on your own accord just
when you were needed.  It really is important to have at least one person
around who REALLY knows what he is doing because as long as humans are
running the band, there will always be emergencies.

Part of the reason that I never chose a protege was that I was so quick
with the program that the prospect of training someone else seemed so
tedious and slow.  Anyway, I urge to find someone who is interested, and
teach that person everything you know before you leave.  Sure, we can
write a manual, but no one is ever going to read it.

One thing that I think is particularly cool is the fact that you, Martin,
and me are all mello players.  I encourage you to find another mello player.

I admit that I have not given the slightest concern to issues of practical
computing in my thinking.  I don't know enough about that subject to have
a worthwhile opinion.  So I'll trust you to tell me when something just
isn't feasible.  However, I hope you'll give all ideas a fair chance and
make an honest effort to find a way to implement them.

Dan


