From: Dan Isaksen <dci@math.uchicago.edu>
Message-Id: <199502230123.TAA17181@zarquon.uchicago.edu>
Subject: fuck the animation order
To: gmeeker@uclink.berkeley.edu
Date: Wed, 22 Feb 1995 19:23:04 -0600 (CST)
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL13]
Content-Type: text
Content-Length: 1007      
Status: RO
X-Status: 


The ratio of complication to usefulness of the animation order concept is
too high.  Let's just chuck that whole idea.  The animation routine uses
the regular stuntsheet order to determine animation.

It will be impossible to do the "jump off the shoulders of the bandsman"
flow, but I don't think that is a major problem.  :)

If you want to have a stuntsheet but you don't want it to appear in the
animation, then make it into a group.  Or if the unanimated stuntsheeet is
a subsheet (like 12C, 12A, 12L in scriptcal), then make it a collection.
You can still print it out since the print routine will be generalized to
allow for arbitrary groups and collections.

This may seem an awkward way to avoid animating unwanted sheets, so most
people are not going to know how to do this.  However, that's no big loss
We've been dealing with the problem for years, and it hasn't caused a
crisis yet.  But the real calchart pros will be able to make their
animation look much slicker by using this trick.

Dan


