I commented the line in bitflip.c with a reference to strtoul, suspecting
that this would cause the routine to behave strangely.  At least the whole
thing finally compiled with this change:

makedepend  -- -I. -Ixlib -Icommon -Iimages  -I/usr/X11R6/include      -DCALCHART_X -DCALCHART_CASESEN -Wall  -- common/main.c common/gui.c common/disk.c  common/config.c xlib/stub.c xlib/images.c  show.c loadshow.c prntshow.c bitflip.c 
gcc -fpcc-struct-return -O2   -I. -Ixlib -Icommon -Iimages  -I/usr/X11R6/include      -DCALCHART_X -DCALCHART_CASESEN -Wall  -target sun4 -c  bitflip.c
bitflip.c: In function `main':
bitflip.c:34: warning: implicit declaration of function `puts'
bitflip.c:13: warning: `val' might be used uninitialized in this function
gcc -fpcc-struct-return -o bitflip -O2      -L/usr/X11R6/lib bitflip.o       

The warning about val is not at all surprising.

Anyway, the program started up fine.  I liked very much your help file. 
It is exactly the kind of thing that Martin and I used to do all the time.

So, the change to bitflip.c had an expectedly severe effect on the running
of the program.  Several times in a row, neither big94 nor sprsh95 would
load.  I got a dialog box saying "cannot load big94.mas".  Then,
mysteriously both shows WOULD load, but the result was a very vibrant
chartreuse filling the window without any other indications.  

I thought this was a rather fascinating bug because it didn't crash the
program; just some very intense and interesting side-effects.  Let me know
if you find a way around the strtoul problem in bitflip.c.

I'll save specific comments on the program for a time when I actually get
it running properly.

Dan


