Content-Length: 868       
Status: RO
X-Status: 


> I think I understand you now.  You're assuming that the zooming is in 
> powers of two?  I'm not sure exactly what is the best way to do it, but 
> that method seems kind of limiting.

No, you've misunderstood me.  When I refer to "grid size," I mean the fact
that the program rounds off locations to the nearest 2-step (or 1-step or
whatever-step) location.  I'm talking about the "G" option in the current
version. 

Grid size should change in powers of two, but zooming can be continuous. 
Divide up all possible magnifications into intervals, and each interval is
assigned a grid size.  For example, 1X to 2X has a 2step grid; 2X to 4X
has a 1step grid; 4X to 8X has a .5step grid; .5X to 1X has a 4step grid;
etc.  The intervals don't have to be exactly these values; I'm just giving
an example of how the grid sizes could be assigned to magnifications.

Dan


