>    It's been a little while, but I'm ready to talk about CalChart again.  
> I started re-coding it in C++ using this platform-independent GUI 
> package.  Eventually it will run under Windows, X, Mac, and whatever 
> other ports are made of this package I'm using.

All right!  We're back in business.  I'm looking forward to hours spent in
the computer room thinking up lengthy detailed unintelligible messages for
you.

>    Anyway, I have questions about how this changes the interface.  Now 
> you can have multiple windows.  The simple thing to do would be to have 
> one window for each show.  But this prevents viewing two different 
> stuntsheets side by side.  Maybe have each loaded show open a new window, 
> but you can also "clone" a window, and you can switch to different shows 
> in memory.  But then you have to explicitly remove a show from memory, 
> and closing a window is something completely different.

Viewing stuntsheets side by side would be a huge asset.  I can remember
more than once having to flip back and forth between two stuntsheets
repeatedly.  Eventually, I got frustrated and just printed out a copy of
one of the two sheets.  Obviously, this is not a good way of doing things.

It seems to me that cloning windows would be the best idea.  Same show,
same memory buffer, but you can look at it from two windows at once.  Is
this what cloning means?  Or splitting windows would also work fine, as
long as you can keep the size of each window reasonably large.

It would also be somewhat useful to be able to view two different shows at
once.  My impression is that the easiest way to handle this situation is
to have "load show" and "create window" be distinct processes.  If you
load a show, it goes into the current window; this is how it will be used
most of the time.  Maybe have an option for creating a new window in which
the loaded show will be put.  If you create a window, it will initially
view the same thing that the "current window" is showing.  

Close a window by choosing to close it.  If all the windows of a show are
closed, then it automatically goes out of memory.  Of course, we'll need a
save Y/N prompt before dropping it from memory.

>    Eventually, the configuration stuff will be editable from within the 
> program, rather than editing a cryptic file (but this isn't high priority 
> right now).

I agree that it is a good idea but not high priority.  Much more important
to get a workable program, then worry about tying up the loose ends and
packaging it nicely.

>    Also, in order to make printing use a platform standard print dialog 
> box (like the standard Windows print popup thing), the stuff that was 
> there before will to be moved.  There should be an option to set the type 
> of the show (standard, spring show) and turning continuity printing on 
> and off should be in the configuration stuff.  Landscape will probably 
> still be in the print popup thing.  Saving EPS files will be a separate 
> menu option.

I had envisioned the type of show (standard, spring show, etc) to be
stored within the data for the show itself.  This data would also be used
to determine what kind of background to put on the stuntsheet editor.

Landscape is an appropriate option for the print popup thing.  Perhaps
overview and turning on and off continuity printing also belongs in the
popup thing, since they don't seem to be of any relevance to the rest of
calchart. 

Also, it is quite reasonable that somebody might want two
versions of a show: one with cont, one without.  Or two versions: one
overview, one normal.  On the other hand, it is quite unlikely for someone
to want two versions: one standard, one spring show format!  Therefore,
the standard/spring show format is really a different kind of question
than overview or continuity/nocontinuity.

>    I'm also wondering if all the icons (the transformation types and 
> whatever) should be moved into a small separate window or appear at the 
> top of every window.  There are also other things like, should animating 
> a show open a new window or appear instead of the stuntsheet.  What about 
> editing continuity?

It would be more space-efficient to have a small separate window for the
icons, but I think it may get confusing if someone is editing in multiple
windows simultaneously.  I think it will become difficult for the user to
keep track of which window he is working on if he has to constantly refer
to a common icon set.   I would say that if you think the icons will fit
reasonably well in each window, then do it that way.

Editing continuity should bring up a new window.  So should animation.  I
can definitely envision someone checking the stuntsheets while also
viewing the animation, or checking stuntsheets while typing continuity, or
checking continuity while viewing animation, or viewing animation while
editing stuntsheets, or viewing animation while editing continuity, .... 
Anyway, this is a quite useful feature.

Imagine this scenario.  The usual situation involves someone working on a
single show.  The user could probably comfortably set up four windows
semi-permanently: two for viewing stuntsheets, one for continuity, and one
for animation.  These windows could stay open all the time, regardless of
what the user is currently working on.  It's just like when I am writing a
math paper, I have one window with a shell for running lpr or latex or
whatever, two or three windows with text editors, and a ps previewer also.
This seems to be a very comfortable way to work.

>    That's about all I can think of right now.  Oh, under Windows, this 
> will probably use MDI (Multiple Document Interface) which is where 
> multiple windows appear inside another window.  This is what Word uses 
> for instance.

Technical details, for which I am not a great help....

Keep the ideas coming!

Dan


