> 1. Some type of scroll bar.  Very slow for the user.
> 2. When the mouse is positioned at the edge of the field, the screen 
> scrolls continuously.  This is means the screen will move when the user 
> goes to click on an icon.
> 3. Scrolling with the keyboard, possibly in conjunction with one of the 
> above options.  This seems pretty un-user-friendly.
> 4. Variation of a scroll bar.  Instead of moving the scroll bar, the user 
> clicks on the border of the field and it scrolls ("arrow" buttons).  
> Doesn't seem particularly fast either.

None of these sound very good.  I would sacrifice the advantages of
multiple windows for the old scrolling method, but there would still be
the problem with selecting icons.  I think we have no choice but to go
with option 2.

However, there are some little ways to soup it up to make it a bit more
efficient.  For example, if you click on a icon immediately after rapidly
passing through the scroll zone, then the scrolling is undone.  Or maybe
make a small time delay so that if you cross the scroll zone very quickly,
then there will be no scrolling at all.

I don't have a very good sense for how this would be to work with.  I'd
really like to try a prototype.  Is it possible to write a small program,
with no capabilities except for scrolling, so that we could see what it
would be like?
 
> That's about all I can think of.  None of them seem perfect.  2 seems the 
> fastest.  I was also thinking of somehow mapping the region the pointer 
> can move in to the portion displayed.  So if the pointer is in the upper 
> left corner of the window, the upper left part of the field is 
> displayed.  If the user moves the pointer to the lower right corner, the 
> screen scrolls to the lower right corner of the field.  But this would 
> make it very difficult to click on a point.  Maybe a certain key press 
> could activate this scrolling method.  Hopefully that made some sense.  
> Hmmm... This might work.  Let me know if you need a clearer explanation.

I understand this, but there is a pretty big disadvantage with this
scheme.  Usually, it is best to center the particular location of interest
so that you can see how things relate on all sides.  With the above plan,
the user would have no control over this; location of points on the screen
would be determined by their location on the field.  For example, points
in the southwest will always appear near the top left corner of the window.

Actually, come to think of it, this might not be so bad.  If possible, I'd
like to give it a try before giving a definitive opinion.

> I was thinking more along the lines of having a picture for a performance 
> at a different stadium.  But I agree this isn't a very big deal.

Whatever.  I guess you could make templates for the Coliseum and the Rose
Bowl if you were really bored and wanted to pretend that you were doing
something useful for the band.  Every time the band went to a bowl, you
could get plans for the stadium ahead of time and print out new tunnel
sheets.  Not terribly useful, but a nice way to "show off" our really cool
adaptable program.

Dan


