From: Dan Isaksen <dci@math.uchicago.edu>
Message-Id: <199509141813.NAA20052@daisy.uchicago.edu>
Subject: continuity language and marching instructions
To: gmeeker@uclink.berkeley.edu
Date: Thu, 14 Sep 1995 13:13:57 -0500 (CDT)
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL13]
Content-Type: text
Content-Length: 4380      
Status: RO
X-Status: 

> Maybe you're right.  But since it seems like Stunt doesn't use genius move
> a lot, they might like it.  However, it may be a bad idea because I wasn't
> planning on making it so you can save shows to the old format (you would
> destroy a lot of the new information I'll be adding and there'd be problems
> like new continuity commands, etc) so if things go bad at a bad time, we
> could be in trouble.  So maybe it's better to finish it first.  I do
> think animating should be a high priority, though.  While Stunt probably
> wouldn't use it just to view shows unless I put in 3D (which is definately
> one of the last things to get done) it is the most complicated part of
> the program and I may need to change other things to get it to work right.
> I want to do away with animation files, so I'll need to spend some time
> thinking about how to animate in realtime.

It seems to me that an attainable deadline to set for yourself is to have
a full-fledged program working for next fall.  That gives you about 11
months to get it working, debug, and put in the finishing touches.  You
could also shoot for spring show, but I think that is rushing things a bit.

Don't worry too much about in what order Stunt wants you to do things.  It
is best to do them in the order that proper programming demands. 
Otherwise, you will end up with a patchwork that is not really most
efficient.

> I agree this can cause some major problems.  It would be nice to only type
> in continuity once, but what Stunt really seem to want is a way to catch
> mistakes in the printed continuity, like writing W instead of E.  I haven't
> thought about the details, but I'm sure it can be done better than it is
> now.  Some options:
> 
> -Have the computer generate somewhat human-readable continuity that Stunt
>  can edit.  Problem is: two different versions.  Make changes and you have
>  to patch things together.
> -Like above, but you can insert pieces that override the default conversion.
> -Just scrap the current animation continuity and create something more
>  like what we see on paper.
> 
> NP can be replaced by "to S.S. n+1," [MTHS E] by MTRM E, as well as
> substituting FMHS/DM for HSDM (in fact the former could be added to the
> continuity grammar), etc.  Other steps need to be added like GV and
> FMSH1/1, and also things can be specified like FMHS NS/EW or FMSH EW/NS
> in the continuity file.  The computer can easily parse things like that.
> You also need to specify where to put measure numbers.  A WYSIWYG editor
> might be nice for that (where measure numbers are in one column and
> you can see the symbols, etc).  Countermarchs can automatically be
> replaced by "HS countermarch as per arrows."  Step N drills are a little
> more complicated, so maybe maybe we need a new command for that.  Like
> a block defining the drill to be done.
> 
> I'm kind of just throwing ideas down, but I think what I'm getting at
> is supplimenting the continuity language (old commands will work, but
> Stunt will probably forget about them).  And then parts can be overriden
> by handwritten continuity for the printed version.  I'm worried a little
> though that Stunt will just do what's easiest to get it printed, and not
> what's going to be easiest to understand.  I'll have to look through some
> old poopsheets and see how much will depart from a standard language.

After thinking about this issue for a while, here is the conclusion I have
come to.  The program will convert continuity commands into readable
marching instructions in the obvious way.  Of course, this option can be
turned off.  Also, the user can manually edit the marching instructions
after they are generated by the program.  One big problem is what to do
when the user edits the instructions, then changes the continuity
commands?  I'm sure we can figure something out for that problem.

Now for the continuity language.  I think we should expand the language to
include lots of synonyms.  For example, FMHSDM and FMHS/DM mean the same
thing as HSDM.  However, I am definitely opposed to allowing "English" to
enter the language.  For example, "to S.S. 5" should NOT be a synonym for
NP.  The problem with allowing English is that there are just too many
ways to punctuate and rearrange words; the program is just too likely to
get confused.  Then stunt will whine that the program is broken.

Dan



