To: gmeeker@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU (Garrick Meeker)
Date: Sat, 16 Sep 1995 12:06:41 -0500 (CDT)
Cc: evidali@uclink2.berkeley.edu
In-Reply-To: <Pine.ULT.3.91.950914231424.24691A-100000@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU> from "Garrick Meeker" at Sep 14, 95 11:31:11 pm
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL13]
Content-Type: text
Content-Length: 4169      
Status: RO
X-Status: 


[Erin: You probably don't care to read about this issue in such detail,
but Gurk mentioned to me that the automatic marching instructions
generator was something that Stunt had specifically requested.]

[Gurk and Erin: See what happens when I get back to Chicago and don't have
enough non-mathematics to do?  I start over-thinking minor issues and
writing longwinded explanations.]
 
Just for clarity, "marching instructions" refers to the text that appears
on the stuntsheets, and "continuity commands" refers to the internal
program's instructions.

I'm still not confident that this automatic marching instructions is a
good idea.  Here is a very specific example.

Let's say that a stuntsheet has 64 beats.  For the first 32, the solidmen
marktime while the plainmen do one of those argyle step2 drills so that
they end up in the same place where they started.  For the last 32,
everybody does a big push towards the east. 

The continuity commands would look something like this:

	PLAIN:				SOL:
		MT STEP(2 2 R1) E		MT 32 E
		FM 4 E				FM 32 E
		FM 4 W
		MT REM-32 E
		FM 32 E

The automatic marching instructions would look something like this:

	1/1	[PLAIN]: Step 2 drill as per arrows [MTHS E before and
			 after you go]
				FMHS 4 E
				FMHS 4 W
		[SOLID]: MTHS 32 E
			 FMHS 32 E

	9/1	[PLAIN]: FMHS 32 E

But the way that the marching instructions SHOULD appear is this:

	1/1	[PLAIN]: Step 2 drill as per arrows [MTHS E before and
			 after you go]
				FMHS 4 E, FMHS 4 W
		[SOLID]: MTHS 32 E

	9/1	ALL: FMHS 32 E
	
There are lots of subtleties like this that the program is going to miss. 
Unless we make the instructions generator very intelligent so that it
looks for commonalities between the various continuity commands for
different symbols, it is never going to be able to handle the concept of
"ALL".

You may think that the first version of the marching instructions is
really just as good as the second version.  But it's not.  The second
version emphasizes the fact that EVERYONE is doing a push at 9/1.  This is
an important piece of information for marchers; they should be able to get
a sense for what the flow is going to be like, just by scanning the
marching instructions.

Of course, sometimes there are very intricate flows, and no matter how you
try to explain it, people will have no idea what is supposed to happen. 
But as a general rule, marching instructions should convey information
about the whole flow.  Not all unambiguous sets of instructions are equal.

Even if we build the program to deal with "ALL", there are going to be
many other problems as well.  How are we ever going to convince ourselves
that we've thought of everything.  We CANNOT depend on Stunt to manually fix
the things that the computer does poorly, because you and I both know that
they will get lazy and won't bother.  

I guess the only way that I would feel comfortable with the automatic
instructions generator is to test it against the last few years' (say 2 or
3 years) stuntsheets.  

We face a dilemma here.  If our generator is not very effective (say
it does the right thing only 50% of the time), then people will be annoyed
with it and won't use it at all.  If our generator is very effective (say
it does the right thing 95% of the time), then people will learn to depend
on it and won't bother to fix it themselves the other 5% of the time.  

The question we have to answer is: does the 5% really make a difference? 
We have to weigh the added convenience to stunt against slightly less
clear marching instructions.  In my opinion, clearer instructions are more
important than stunt's convenience.

Here are some arguments that you can use to convince Stunt.  Tell them
that their professional expertise is so finely honed that no computer
could ever match them in their ability to write marching instructions. 
Tell them that if their job gets too easy, then bandsmen will notice that
they aren't working very hard and they will lose respect and prestige.

I'm just not comfortable with the idea of a program writing prose.  To me,
marching instructions are essentially that.  They are NOT merely a list of
unambiguous commands.

Dan



