Here are some of the observations I've made so far.  By no means am I 
finished testing this version.  If you don't understand what I'm talking 
about or can't reproduce these, let me know.

>   I have a version of calchart for you.  It's on soda as 
> ~gmeeker/calchart/chartsunos....  Let me know if you can run it.  I tried 
> running it on the band's computer and the entire system crashed, so 
> there's got to be a bug in the OS (we're still using SunOS 4.1.1).  
> Anyway, a lot of things are partially implemented but don't completely 
> work.  Here's a partial list of things you haven't seen yet:

Calchart hasn't (yet) caused the system to crash, so I guess that's a 
good sign.
 
> movement of points (block move only)

I couldn't figure out how to move blocks.  I could only move one point at
a time.

> undo

How far back can you go with undos?  Up to the most recent save?  There
should be a warning message when you reach the point where there are no
more dos to undo.

There should be a way to undo an undo.

> springshow mode

Zellerbach grid should go out to the 35s, except in the front where they
only go to the 40s.  See spring show stuntsheets for the correct shape.

> changing number of points, labels

Since it is absolutely necessary that the first thing a user does is create
some points with the show info box, perhaps the show info box should
automatically appear when you make a new show.

The points per letter variable does not do the right thing.  Most of the 
time I couldn't get it to do anything besides 10 per letter, even though 
the displayed value was smaller.  Once I managed to get it to do 1 per 
letter, but I couldn't reproduce that.

There should be a block spacing option when creating new points.  Perhaps
there should also be a location option.

> changing symbols, label positions

Slashes should be thicker.  I can hardly see them.

Use something other than A0 for the label icons.  I was thinking you were
talking about rays and lines for a while.  If you use a number that is
not possible to be mistaken for a letter (like 3), that would be better.
Is there anything we could do that is clever or cute here?

Number labels start with 0, not 1.  This is not a big problem, but it
does not conform with stunt's conventions.

> grid
> multiple windows (changes in one window are shown in other windows and 
>      any number of any window can be opened, so you can open multiple
>      animation windows, etc.)
> editing printed continuity (only displayed)
> editing animation continuity (edits aren't used, continuities can't be 
>      created or deleted)
> animation (many commands don't work, backwards playback is buggy)

My version doesn't even have a backwards play option.

There should be icons to jump to beginning and end and to sheets by name.

Need to be able to hold "next beat" for long-distance scrolling.

> deletion and copying of stuntsheets
> 
> So I guess let me know if you can run it, any bugs you find, and of 
> course, any suggestions about the user interface.

There are some funny things going on when you use the points-per-letter and 
zoom slides.  They jump all over the place.  This causes trouble in using 
the slide to set the value.  Grid moves around, too.

When I use the points-per-letter slide, I get funny green dashed lines all
over the place.

What is the text box within the showinfo box for?

Using the slide to set the zoom value does change the magnification, but it
does not cause the displayed number to change.  Also, non-integer values
for zooming do not get corrected.  For example, if I type "5a" for zoom, the
window goes to zoom level 5, but the displayed value is still "5a".

I get confused when using the buttons with the pulldown menus.  Only the
right button gives the pulldown menu.  The left button automatically
selects the first option on the pulldown menu.  This is a pretty big
problem because the first option on the file menu is "new show".  Several
times I accidentally erased stuff because of this.  Is this just an
artifact of the version I am using, or what?

When you set a title, the old title should be displayed for editing.
Add a button to erase the entry.

Sheet titles probably should not be copied when making new stuntsheets.  
A good choice for default name would be the number of the sheet.

At large zoom sizes, I can't view the entire field, even if I scroll.  The
scroll bars need to be recalibrated or something when the zoom size changes.

Need ticks along the sideline.  Maybe the numbers should be further from
the sideline; I'm not sure about that.

Pro field hashes are 18ft6in apart, not 22ft6in apart like you show.  Is 
this a problem?

What should the values for zoom, grid, and so forth be when you 
open a new window?  Default values, or same as what they just are in 
the parent window?  It seems like same as what they are in the parent 
window is a good idea.

Saving an unnamed show (with "Save", not "Save as...") causes the program 
to crash.

Redrawing needs to be limited to the affected regions of the field, not 
the whole screen.  Too much flashing right now.

If you type a new value for grid or zoom but don't hit return, nothing 
changes.  This is different than other things like number of points, 
where you click on an apply button.  We need to unify the conventions 
somehow.

Dan


