> This is the way XView applications work.  I think I can compile a Motif 
> version for you, which is much more user-friendly, but the executable 
> will be bigger because you don't have the Motif library.  Anyway, XView 

Don't worry about problems that are XView-local.  The important thing is 
that it works well with MS-Windows, since that is going to be the 
platform for the foreseeable future.

> > Sheet titles probably should not be copied when making new stuntsheets.  
> > A good choice for default name would be the number of the sheet.
> > 
> Good idea.

Actually, the correct algorithm is a bit more complicated.  I believe we 
talked about this a long time ago.  Adding a sheet to the end of the show 
should cause the new name to be "n+1", where "n" is the name of the old 
last sheet.  Adding a sheet to the beginning makes "n-1", where "n" is 
the name of the old first sheet.  Adding a sheet between "n" and "n+1" 
makes the name "na".  Of course, if the nearby sheet titles are not 
integers, then just put the number of the sheet as the name.  Is this too 
tricky to implement?  It may sound complicated, but I think it would save 
the user a lot of time.
 
> > At large zoom sizes, I can't view the entire field, even if I scroll.  The
> > scroll bars need to be recalibrated or something when the zoom size changes.
> > 
> There's a bug in the scroll bar setting code.  I haven't exactly figured 
> out why (I think I'll have to look at the wxWindows source).

Again, don't worry too much about wxWindows-local problems.
 
> > Need ticks along the sideline.  Maybe the numbers should be further from
> > the sideline; I'm not sure about that.
> > 
> Do ticks on the sideline really matter?  Aside from being more like the 
> real field, I'm not sure why you want them.  I don't print them on the 
> stuntsheets and no one's complained.

I don't see why they shouldn't be there.  If they are on the field, then 
they should be on the stuntsheet.  I am inclined to print the big yard 
numbers, too.  But that gets difficult with colors and stuff like that.

> > Pro field hashes are 18ft6in apart, not 22ft6in apart like you show.  Is 
> > this a problem?
> > 
> This was the way we practiced for the 49er game.  I thought it was lame 
> and that we should either ignore the hashes or use an odd number of steps 
> between them, but I guess people look at the field too much (e.g. 
> ticks).

If that's how it's practiced, then that's how you should print them.

> Anyway, thanks for your suggestions.  Other than bug fixes, I'm going to 
