Bugs for the 011896 version.

I got segmentation faults when I tried to load big94.mas, ewf6.mas, or
sprsh95.mas (I downloaded them from your soda directory).  Also, big94.tar
is incomplete or something.  This means that I can't yet test much in the
edit-continuity and animation line.  Until I can load an already-existing
show, I've pretty much tested everything that I can right now. 

Whenever you change the magnification, the view jumps to the southwest
corner.  Probably it should preserve the center, unless the entire field
will now fit into the view.

Reducing the number of points causes an arbitrary set of points to be 
deleted.  The user should be able to select which points get erased.

The points-per-letter variable seems to be working fine now.

The word "Tempo" is placed partially off the edge of the animation window.

The tempo slide in the animation window does not work.  You can type a 
number manually, but you can't adjust it with the slide.  Strange, 
because it was working in the 011596 version.

I like how selecting points shows up on all sheets.  I think this is the 
right way to do it.  I tested things like looking at two different 
stuntsheets of the same show at once, and blockmoving points on one of the 
sheets.  The points on the other sheet did not move, which is what is 
supposed to happen.

I'm getting messages like "Deleting window from list of 3 elements." in 
my shell window whenever I close a window.  These messages should be 
surpressed somehow.

Is it going to be a problem that more than one show info window can be
opened for the same show?  I tried creating some kind of contradiction,
but everything seemed to work.  The only trouble I could find was that the
information in the second box does not get updated when you apply changes
in the first show info box.  This does not cause any disasters, but it 
can get confusing when different boxes are showing different information.

Windows need to be labeled better to keep track of things when more than 
one show is being displayed.  Need to cross-label show-info, animation, 
and edit-continuity windows so that the user knows which window goes with 
which show.

Do the show-info, animation, and continuity windows have to die when the 
main window is closed?  I can foresee a situation where you want to copy 
continuity but don't care about the view of the field.  In order to 
reduce cluttering in the workspace, it might be convenient to get rid of 
the main window.

> Well, this can be changed in the configuration file, so I'm not going to 
> worry about it.  But having a stage that isn't rectangular like the 
> spring show stuntsheets two years ago IS a problem.

Fortunately, every (finite) stage is contained in some rectangle.  So 
stunt can just ignore the corners if necessary.
 
> This should be pretty easy, and I agree it will be helpful.  But what if 
> you try to add a stuntsheet before "1" or "0"?  Should it name it "1"?

I'd say that "0" comes before "1", and "-1" comes before "0".  If I were 
on stunt and had to add two sheets to the beginning of a show, I would 
call them "-1" and "0".  But maybe not everyone thinks like me.
 
> > Again, don't worry too much about wxWindows-local problems.
> >  
> wxWindows is the library that allows me to compile under different 
> platforms.  XView is an X Window library.  This scrollbar problem shows 
> up under MS-Windows also.

This confusion is caused by my ignorance; sorry.  I think I understand now.
 
> > I don't see why they shouldn't be there.  If they are on the field, then 
> > they should be on the stuntsheet.  I am inclined to print the big yard 
> > numbers, too.  But that gets difficult with colors and stuff like that.
> > 
> Maybe it would even be more readable on the printed stuntsheets to have 
> the big yard numbers in a light grey.  People would definately catch when 
> the field is shifted for a page.  Also I need to handle printing to the 
> -10, since full field spread for 169 goes out that far.

I like the idea of displaying the large numbers, if you think it is 
possible to create a readable printed sheet.  Presumably it would help 
bandsmen with alignment, too.  Beware that the size and shape of the 
numbers do change on different fields.  Obviously, you should design 
yours to match Memorial.

Why not add endzones to the on-screen display?  You could have some fun 
with it by writing "GOLDEN BEARS" in it.  Or maybe make it optional.
 
> You can try the version with the fixed scrollbars and list boxes in the 
> meantime.

Presumably you mean fixed sliders?  Because the scrolling still isn't
working.  This is probably a silly question, but what do you mean by "list
boxes"? 

Dan


