All of the other sliders work fine.  If I type in a tempo and press 
ENTER, the position of the slider changes to match the new tempo and the 
speed of animation does in fact change.  However, if I try to drag the 
slider around, nothing happens.  Actually, sometimes it changes the tempo 
by one or two, but I can't get it to do that consistently.

I was fooling around with this again, and I noticed one other thing about 
animation.  If you change the tempo while the animation is playing, the 
speed is not affected.  You have to press stop, and then start playing 
again to get the animation to run at the new speed.  [This is the kind of 
bug where I feel like I am useful; it's not such an obvious thing, but it 
ought to be done right.]

> > I like how selecting points shows up on all sheets.  I think this is the 
> > right way to do it.  I tested things like looking at two different 
> > stuntsheets of the same show at once, and blockmoving points on one of the 
> > sheets.  The points on the other sheet did not move, which is what is 
> > supposed to happen.
> > 
> This isn't clear.  I assume you mean it's behaving correctly?

Don't worry about it.  Everything is fine.
 
> > Do the show-info, animation, and continuity windows have to die when the 
> > main window is closed?  I can foresee a situation where you want to copy 
> > continuity but don't care about the view of the field.  In order to 
> > reduce cluttering in the workspace, it might be convenient to get rid of 
> > the main window.
> > 
> It's possible, but it would require some big changes.  For one thing, all 
> the menus are on the field window.  One thing that isn't very clear is 
> which window is the parent of these subwindows.  If you load a new show 
> from a field window, all of its children windows will now show the new 
> show.  And if you close it, its children will close.  But you can't tell 
> offhand which ones are the children.  But this inheritance is useful.  
> When you change the current stuntsheet on the field window, the 
> continuity editors are updated.  Hope I explained that clearly.

Now that I think about it, I see the problem with having a continuity 
window open without the field window also.  The big issue are the menus on 
the field window.

It seems to me that the parent/child relationship is working as it 
should.  I like the fact that when you create a new field window, it does 
not really behave like a child of the original field window.  That is, 
when you close the first field window, the new one stays open. 

With better labels for the various windows, it will be clear which child
windows go with which parents windows. 

> > Fortunately, every (finite) stage is contained in some rectangle.  So 
> > stunt can just ignore the corners if necessary.
> >  
> The problem is for printing.  For some stages, you might not want to 
> print all of the lines because they'll extend into the drawing of the stage.

Did I ever tell you what we did the first year for Zellerbach.  We 
printed the show on the old Harmon sheets.  We took a piece of paper with 
the outline of the Zellerbach stage on it (ie., the walls, edge of stage, 
and so forth) and cut a hole in it to match the shape of the grid that we 
wanted.  Then we put this template over the Harmon-style sheets and 
photocopied one at a time.  It was a bit of a hassle, but it actually 
worked very well.
 
> > I like the idea of displaying the large numbers, if you think it is 
> > possible to create a readable printed sheet.  Presumably it would help 
> > bandsmen with alignment, too.  Beware that the size and shape of the 
> > numbers do change on different fields.  Obviously, you should design 
> > yours to match Memorial.
> > 
> I'll worry about this later, like this summer.

I hope you are saving these ideas somewhere.
 
