> Actually, I've been asked to "flip" several shows for stunt.  I had to 
> for spring show this year after we decided to turn the poopsheets 
> around.  I think the only other time was for Mary's show.  She had 
> charted it to the east so she could visualize it better.  She then asked 
> me if there was any way to avoid re-entering the entire show.  So I 
> rewrote a quick program that turned the formations around.  The 
> complicated part is the continuity.  I just edited it by hand in these 
> two instances, but doing it automatically should be possible, but it 
> would have to parse the continuity as per animation and then generate the 
> new continuity text.  Changing the printed continuity is practically 
> impossible, since it is just english text, and who knows what references 
> to direction will be in there.  I suppose you could replace isolated W's 
> with E's and so forth, but it won't be perfect.  Perhaps it would be 
> better to just change the view point.  I was planning on being able to 
> view animations and stuntsheets from either side, and I could do the same 
> for printing.  For printed continuity, there could be a special code for 
> each direction that will be replaced with the correct direction.  How 
> does this sound?  It elimates the need to fiddle with the animation 
> continuity anyway.

I also had to flip a show once or twice during my tenure.

What do you mean by "special code"?  I think you mean that the user types 
something like "\E" as a shorthand notation for "east".  Then the 
flipping routine would not actually change any data; it would just 
reinterpret "\E" to mean "west".
This is not a bad idea, but there are other things, such as NSEW, that 
will also have to be marked with special codes.

Are there any other uses for the special codes?  Flipping is not such a
common thing; it doesn't seem worthwhile to type all those special codes
all the time just in case you later decide to flip the show. 

Maybe we should use a special code to mark the fact that what follows is
"normal text". 

Here are two examples of what I mean.  The first has directions and 
commands as special codes, and the second has "normal text" marked specially.

Example 1:
	FMHS \NSEW \NP [\MTHS \E]

	Step 2 drill as per arrows [MTHS E before and after you go]
		FMHS \4 \N, FMHS \4 \S

Example 2:
	NSEW NP [MTHS E]

	{Step 2 drill as per arrows [MTHS E before and after you go]}
		FMHS 4 N {,} FMHS 4 S


Dan



