I have looked at both versions a bit, and I have already noticed a few 
bugs that occur with one version but not the other.  Most of the bugs 
that I have already found occur in both versions.  So if you want to 
claim to be supporting both versions, then you had best continue to make 
both versions available so that I can find bugs.

I don't have an opinion about the importance of supporting both Motif and 
XView because I don't know the technical differences.  So, you should 
decide whether you want to continue to support both or not.  Maybe you 
could make only one available most of the time, but once in a while you 
should make both available.

I will send you a bug report by the end of the week.

Dan


From dci@math.uchicago.edu Wed Apr 17 07:46:01 1996
Received: from harvey.calband.berkeley.edu (harvey.CalBand.Berkeley.EDU [128.32.89.167]) by pasteur.EECS.Berkeley.EDU (8.6.11/8.6.4) with ESMTP id HAA05349 for <gmeeker@pasteur.eecs.berkeley.edu>; Wed, 17 Apr 1996 07:46:00 -0700
Received: from hog.uchicago.edu (hog.uchicago.edu [128.135.72.46]) by harvey.calband.berkeley.edu (8.6.12/8.6.12) with ESMTP id HAA27618 for <gmeeker@calband.berkeley.edu>; Wed, 17 Apr 1996 07:45:00 -0700
Received: (from dci@localhost) by hog.uchicago.edu (8.6.11/8.6.10) id JAA10513 for gmeeker@calband.berkeley.edu; Wed, 17 Apr 1996 09:46:06 -0500
From: Dan Isaksen <dci@math.uchicago.edu>
Message-Id: <199604171446.JAA10513@hog.uchicago.edu>
Subject: calchart bugs
To: gmeeker@CalBand.Berkeley.EDU
Date: Wed, 17 Apr 1996 09:46:05 -0500 (CDT)
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL25]
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Length: 7204      
Status: RO
X-Status: 


Here is a preliminary list of bugs that I have found.  It is far from 
complete; there are many features that I haven't played with thoroughly yet.

All the bugs listed apply to the Motif version.  Probably they also apply 
to the XView version, but I haven't explicitly tested them.  However, the 
ones marked XV have been reproduced on the XView version.

I am particularly proud of my work on number 18 (see below).

1(XV). When I select "help", I get a message in my shell window saying that 
the program cannot find "wxhelp"; this is the problem that you told me 
would occur.  However, the program freezes; then a dialog box appears 
with a warning about "timing out after 15 seconds".  After I close the 
dialog box, the whole process starts all over again.  The only recourse 
is to kill the process externally.

2(XV). Loading a show still results in a seg fault.

3(XV). Extraneous "Deleting show...." messages in my shell window.  Are 
these useful for debugging?  Just don't forget to get rid of them eventually.

4. Extraneous "Deleting window from list of n elements." messages in my 
shell window.  

5.  In the show info box, click on a letter, then scroll.  Funny things 
happen to the dotted lines.

6.  Text editing is fucked up.  Control characters create nonstandard 
symbols, backspace doesn't work, etc.  This applies in such places as: 
setting the number of points in the show info box; the text box at the 
bottom of the show info box; typing how many rows you want in your 
initial formation; etc.

7.  (XV) Having to press ENTER to change the number of points is
illogical.  I believe we discussed this a while ago.  When I started
testing again recently, I couldn't figure out how to add points for quite
a while.  Eventually, I stumbled across the answer.  Anyway, the current
system is too confusing; if I can't figure it out, can you imagine how
confused Stunt will be? 

8.  If you type text in the box at the bottom of the show info box, it 
doesn't reappear when you open the show info box again.

9.  (XV) There is an ambiguity in the name "Show info".  Do you mean it 
as an adjective and noun (ie, "information pertaining to this show")
or do you mean it as a verb and noun (ie, "put the information on the 
screen")?  Can we think of a non-ambiguous synonym?

10.  If two points get put on top of each other, they can later be 
separated by using individual move.  In version 2, the program made an
arbitrary choice as to which point you would be picking up.  It told you 
which one it had selected for you at the bottom of the screen.  Something 
analogous should happen in version 3.  Maybe the program should ask you 
which one you want; at the very least it should tell you which one you've 
got.

11.  Auto relabeling is of course very useful.  But there is potentially 
a time for manual relabeling.  What if I am experimenting, and the points 
get all jumbled up so that there is no nice consecutive pattern to the 
labeling?  Even if I relabel, the labels will still be in the same 
illogical order.  It should be possible to straighten out the pattern, 
even if it requires a lot of manual work.

What I am talking about is the fact that the labels in the pregame wedge 
are in a nice pattern; usually the first page of a halftime show is the 
same way.

12.  You can't undo immediately after an undo.  Why not be able to undo 
an undo operation?  Or do something like emacs and be able to undo the 
last n operations.

13.  When moving individual points, I am slightly bothered by the fact 
that the drawn line moves continuously rather than snapping to the grid.  
It really ought to snap to the grid, since that better reflects what the 
move is actually going to be.  Unless of course you have selected no 
grid, in which case it is fine to move continuously.

14.  Saving seems to work, in the sense that a file is created.  However, 
loading it results in a seg fault (see 2).

15.  The points-per-letter slide in the show info box is too short.  Tiny 
movements of one pixel can cause the number to change by more than one.

16.  Lots and lots of warnings in my shell window.  We already talked 
about these.

17.  There are problems with refreshing the screen far away from the 
field proper.  This only occurs when your window is much bigger than the 
entire field (for example, at very low zoom sizes).

When you switch to spring show mode, the screen is not refreshed 
properly.  Changing the zoom size was the only way I could find to force 
it to refresh.

If you put points far far away from the football field then remove them 
by reducing the number of points on the show info grid, they don't get 
erased.  Of course they don't exist anymore, but they still appear on screen.

I suspect that both of these problems are symptoms of the same bug.

18.  Although the set of possible locations for points is theoretically
infinite, the region that you are capable of seeing is bounded by the size
of your monitor.  If a point lies over your "horizon", you can never get
it back.  Of course, there's no way to get the points over your "horizon"
in the first place.  Or is there?  I have found two ways.

Let's say you add 1000 points and choose to have only one point per 
row.  This will create a really long line along the south endzone.  It 
will spill far off the field, and probably off the screen unless you have 
a very big window. 

The other way is to use block move.  Blockmove a line of points by 
indicating where one end will go.  It is possible to manuever the other 
end over the horizon.

If you use the second trick on the top edge of the window, the points 
will be displayed as piled up along the edge of the window.  Although 
they are displayed there, they aren't actually there.  Their actual 
location is exactly where they ought to have been translated into the 
"negative" region of the plane.

You may wonder how I know what their actual location is when they are off 
in unviewable "negative land".  If you block select points and your 
rectangle spills out of your window, it affects the selected region even 
if it isn't displayed.  I used this fact to gain information about the 
locations of the undisplayed points.  Pretty clever, huh?

I think the ideal solution to this problem is this.  When points are very
far away from the football field, the scrolling routines should recognize
this and allow you to scroll that far.  This solution still provides for
the theoretically infinite plane, which is a nice thing.  And it avoids
the obstruction of the "horizon" that I talked about. 

One problem with this suggestion is that it still is not easy to put a 
point very far away.  (Don't ask why you would ever want to set a point 
out in the parking lot outside the stadium :) )  There should be a way to 
tell the scrolling routines to let me go a certain prescribed distance, 
even though there aren't points out there yet.

19.  It's impossible to use letter labels with more than 260 points.  Is 
it worthwhile inventing a scheme with double letters (AA, BB, etc.)?  Or 
should we just forget about it and expect that the band will never get 
that big?  Certainly there do exist bands that are that big.




